<HEADLINE> South Korean Tycoon Makes Cattle Drive to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, June 16 (Xinhua) -- South Korean business tycoon
Chung Ju-Yung handed over 500 head of cattle at his hometown in
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) Tuesday in a
gesture of unity and reconciliation between the two sides of the
Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The 83-year-old founder of Hyundai Group crossed the Military
Demarcation Line (MDL) Tuesday morning with a convoy of 50 Hyundai
trucks carrying the cattle to Tongchon, where he was born.
</P>
<P>
"I am so happy to visit my hometown. I am so happy to go to my
birthplace in my car," said Chung before going on to meet DPRK
official, including Kim Yong Sun, chairman of the Korean
Asia-Pacific Peace Committee (KAPPC).
</P>
<P>
Chung had offered to donate 1,000 head of cattle and 50,000
tons of maize to the famine-hit DPRK. The rest of the donation
will be delivered after consultations on the route and schedule
are completed between the Red Cross organizations of the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The Korean Central News Agency reported that Chung and Kim held
talks in "an atmosphere of compatriotic feelings" at Mansudae
Assembly Hall. Also present were KAPPC Vice-Chairman Song Ho Gyong
and other officials.
</P>
<P>
Chung and his party were warmly greeted at Panmunjon by Song
and Jong Un-Op, chairman of the National Economic Cooperation
Federation.
</P>
<P>
Chung is the first South Korean businessman to have entered the
DPRK via Panmunjon, a small village lying on the MDL where the
truce ending the 1950-53 war was signed, a half century after the
division of the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the cattle drive, Panmunjon had never been used as a
route for the intra-Korean private visits and the transportation
of commodities.
</P>
<P>
Chung, who made another trip to the DPRK in 1989, said he would
also explore the possibility of a tourism resort at Kumkang
Mountain and the prospects of economic cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
