<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Fed Chief Calls for Free-Market View of Giant Mergers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan Tuesday urged Congress to take free-market
view of recent wave of multibillion-dollar mergers and be cautious
in substituting government regulations for the giant mergers.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan made the remarks during a hearing at the Senate
Judiciary Committee, which seeks to determine how the recent spate
of mergers in banking and other industries would affect the U.S.
consumers and the economy overall.
</P>
<P>
"The United States is currently experiencing its fifth major
corporate consolidation of this century," Greenspan told the
committee. "When trying to understand and deciding how to react to
this development, I would hope that we appropriately account for
the complexity and dynamism of modern free markets."
</P>
<P>
Greenspan said the first merger wave occurred at the turn of
the century, followed by other waves in the late 1920s, the late
1960s and the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The first two merger waves produced significant increases in
economic concentration in the manufacturing sector, the Fed chief
noted. He added that there was no sign recent rounds of mergers
have had much effect in further consolidating manufacturing
companies, reflecting that they are occurring in a U.S. economy
that is already at an advanced stage of development.
</P>
<P>
"The effects of the present merger wave on concentration have
yet to be determined, but there is little reason to expect their
influence will differ substantially from the merger wave of the
early 1980s, which produced at most a slight increase in
manufacturing concentration," Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
Some U.S. lawmakers have expressed concerns that a number of
big bank mergers could force consumers to pay higher bank fees as
a result of reduced competition.
</P>
<P>
But Greenspan said while the wave of bank mergers had reduced
the level of banks nationally, the number competing in any given
region of the country remained about the same.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the local banking competitors now "tend to
be the same competitors in an increasing number of markets."
</P>
<P>
Asked about the economic impact, Greenspan said there would
clearly be job losses as banks consolidate branches, but he said a
growing U.S. economy should be able to handle the displaced
workers. He noted that 300,000 workers lose their jobs each week
but despite this fact, the unemployment rate still remains at a
28-year low of 4.3 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
