<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Former Prime Minister on the Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Alain Juppe, visiting mayor of
Bordeaux and former Prime Minister of France, predicted here
Tuesday that the Euro will become one of the leading international
currencies of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a conference attended by about 200 Hong Kong and
French entrepreneurs, Juppe said the Euro, as a fundamental phase
in European integration, is the outcome of years of work which
called for outstanding energy and political will from its heads of
government.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the economic potential of a unified Europe is
comparable to that of the United States and greater than that of
Japan.
</P>
<P>
With 290 million inhabitants, or six percent of the world's
population, the Monetary Union with its 15 members represents 20
percent of the world's GDP and a similar share of the world's
trade.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of statistics for 1996, Juppe said that the share
of the European Union in the GDP of the OECD countries stands at
38.3 percent compared to 32.5 percent for the United States and
20.5 percent for Japan.
</P>
<P>
Setting aside intra-community trade, the share of the European
Union in world trade stands at 21 percent compared to 19.6 percent
for the United States and 10.5 percent for Japan.
</P>
<P>
"Europe is therefore one of the world's leading economic
powers, and the Euro will make it possible to transpose on to the
monetary plane an economic capacity which hitherto was unable to
find its true expression on the international financial markets,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"I am personally convinced that this economic power will be
consolidated even further within the next few years, thanks to the
Euro," he said.
</P>
<P>
This is firstly because that the European Union countries will
be obliged to coordinate their economic and budgetary policies to
ensure their convergence.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, "the Euro zone will form an incredible single
market of some 300 million consumers, a veritable source of future
development for our firms."
</P>
<P>
Finally, competitive devaluations and unforeseeable swings in
exchange rates, which always impact competitivity, growth and
therefore employment, will no longer be possible.
</P>
<P>
On the monetary plane, the Euro therefore spells out the
economic and commercial power of Europe, but also stands as the
guarantor of the conditions of stability and transparency required
for its development, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Euro will, in the future, be a stable and firm
currency, capable of being the preferred instrument of
international transactions and an international monetary tool as
well.
</P>
<P>
After his arrival in Hong Kong on Tuesday morning, Juppe
attended an opening ceremony of the first International Wine and
Spirits Exhibition for the Asia-pacific region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
