<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1530 GMT, June 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) on Tuesday
confirmed it will further cut its oil production to support the
Amsterdam agreement signed by other three major oil producers
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
UAE Minister of Petroleum and Mineral Resources Obeid bin Saif
Al Nasir made the confirmation before his departure Tuesday for
Riyadh, Saudi Arabia to attend the meeting of the ministerial
petroleum cooperation committee of the Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) member states, due to start later in the day.
</P>
<P>
The UAE had decided to cut petroleum production by 125,000
barrels per day as from April 1, in the wake of the Riyadh accord
signed by Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Mexico on March 22 to
bolster up petroleum prices in the world market. (UAE-Oil
Production-Cut)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin announced here
Tuesday that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic has agreed to
negotiate with ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"The whole world should see what we agreed upon so that there
will be no retreating," said Yeltsin, who met with Milosevic
Tuesday morning in the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said he talked with U.S. President Bill Clinton Monday
night and the two discussed "how to remove the Balkan thorn and
resolve the problem of Kosovo". (Yeltsin-Milosevic-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Canadian warplanes will join the NATO's military
exercises near Kosovo, the Globe and Mail newspaper reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The deployment of Canadian warplanes, which were absent from
NATO's initial show of force near Kosovo Monday, was approved by
the cabinet on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Six Canadian CF-18s are expected to be shepherded across the
Atlantic to the Aviano airbase in Italy by a U.S. Air Force KC-10
tanker either late Thursday or early Friday. (Canada-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korean business tycoon Chung Ju-Yung Tuesday
morning entered the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
by crossing the Military Demarcation Line (MDL) on foot at the
truce village of Panmunjon.
</P>
<P>
"I am so happy to visit my hometown. I am so happy to go to my
birthplace in my car," said the 83-year-old founder of Hyundai
Group, who was born in what is now the DPRK's Tongchon, before he
crossed the MDL with his donation of 500 head of cattle loaded on
50 Hyundai trucks.
</P>
<P>
He had offered to donate a total of 1,000 head of cattle and
50,000 tons of maize to the DPRK. The rest of the donation will be
delivered after consultations on the route and schedule between
the Red Cross organizations of the two sides complete.
(SKorea-DPRK-Visit) 
