<HEADLINE> Milosevic: Belgrade Ready for Political Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic pledged here Tuesday that Belgrade is ready to settle
the Kosovo issue through political means.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement reached after talks between Milosevic and
Russian President Boris Yeltsin said Belgrade has made a
commitment to resume talks with leaders of ethnic Albanians in its
Kosovo region
</P>
<P>
The statement said talks on all issues concerning Kosovo,
including possible forms of an autonomous status for the area,
will be held uninterruptedly in accordance with a schedule
approved by the sides and in line with international standards,
the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders reaffirmed the need to preserve Yugoslavia's
territorial integrity and condemned any manifestations of
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
It also guaranteed employees of the International Committee of
the Red Cross and the Office of the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees free access to Yugoslav areas and unhindered delivery of
humanitarian aid to the regions.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that Yugoslav government forces will reduce
their presence in Kosovo as terrorist activity diminishes.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo is a region within the Yugoslav republic of Serbia where
ethnic Albanians, who account for 90 percent of the population
there, are demanding independence.
</P>
<P>
More than 250 people have died since military conflict between
government troops and the Kosovo Liberation Army, the armed wing
of the Albanian independence movement, broke out in February.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic, for his part, welcomed "Russia's clearly expressed
stand" against sanctions on Yugoslavia and in favor of restoring
Yugoslavia's membership in international organizations.
</P>
<P>
Belgrade is ready to begin talks with the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe on the establishment of an OSCE
mission in Kosovo and reinstating Yugoslavia within the
organization.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
