<HEADLINE> Laser Depilation Works for Girl With Hirsute Affliction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Liu Hua, a 17-year old girl
suffering from a hirsute affliction, today received the first
session of laser depilation treatment.
</P>
<P>
The operation was carried out at the No.9 Hospital attached to
the city's No.2 Medical University, and experts said that the girl
will look normal after four such operations over the next six
months.
</P>
<P>
Liu, from northeast China's Liaoning Province, was born normal,
but her skin turned black and thick hair grew in many parts of her
body.
</P>
<P>
The hospital learned about the girl and her anguish that she
was different from other girls from a newspaper report.
</P>
<P>
The hospital administration decided to carry out the
operations free of charge, the country's first treatment using
laser depilation for a hirsute affliction patient.
</P>
<P>
To protect the skin, the depilation will keep the sweat and
sebaceous glands sound while only removing the hair, according to
the hospital.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNEP Calls for Enforced Battle Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Chief of the United Nations
Environment Program Klaus Topfer called for worldwide enforced
battle against desertification Tuesday, one day before the World
Day to Combat Desertification.
</P>
<P>
"Desertification remains the leading environmental problem of
the world's dry lands," Topfer said. "Its effects are manifested
socially."
</P>
<P>
"Most of the failure of dry lands management schemes can be
attributed to the adoption of a top-down approach to development,
ignorance of local systems, short time horizons and use of
complicated, difficult-to-maintain systems," said Topfer.
</P>
<P>
The latest U.N. data estimate that now desertification affects
about 3.6 billion hectares -- 70 percent of the global dry lands,
or a quarter of the total land areas of the world excluding the
naturally hyper-arid deserts and Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
Thus, it puts at risk more than one billion people in over one
hundred countries -- about a sixth of the world's population,
said Till Darnhoffer, a senior official in charge of UNEP
projects in this field.
</P>
<P>
In Africa, 73 percent of the the dry lands shows signs of
desertification, said Darnhoffer.
</P>
<P>
He said rough estimations also indicate that the value of the
income foregone annually due to desertification is about 42
billion U.S. Dollars worldwide and in Africa alone 9.3 billion
U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The overall cost of desertification of developing countries
stands at six to 14.6 billion U.S. Dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
Desertification means land degradation in arid, semi-arid and
dry sub-humid areas resulting from mainly man-made activities and
climatic variations. It is different from "desert expansion"
caused by climatic fluctuations on vegetation productivity at
desert fringes, said Darnhoffer.
</P>
<P>
"Desertification is both an environmental problem and a
development problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
On June 17, 1994, the Convention to Combat Desertification was
adopted in Paris.
</P>
<P>
So far, a total of 125 countries have ratified or acceded to
the convention. The United States, Russia and Australia are
among those who have still to join.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
