<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Housing Starts Drop 0.7 Pct in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Housing construction
in May slid slightly for the third straight month, but building
activity continues to be considerably strong, the Commerce
Department reported here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In May, builders started construction of new housing units at a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.53 million units, down 0.7
percent from March, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
Construction also slowed a bit in March and April after hitting
a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.62 million units in
February, the best in over 9 years.
</P>
<P>
Including May, home building has now stayed above the 1.5
million unit rate for nine straight months, a stretch never seen
since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
For the first five months of this year, housing starts have
been 6.4 percent higher than the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that strong economic growth, low unemployment
and mortgage rates helped new home sales hit a record high in
April. Along with home builders, furniture and appliance
manufacturers, architectural firms and landscaping companies are
benefiting from the buying boom.
</P>
<P>
New construction of single-family homes was down a tiny 0.4
percent in May, to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.23
million units. Meanwhile, apartment building starts were down 1.9
percent, to 302,000 units. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Prices Pick Up 0.3 Pct in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. prices increases for
lettuce, cigarettes, gasoline and prescription drugs pushed up
consumer inflation by 0.3 percent in May, the Labor Department
reported here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Though moderate, the seasonally adjusted increase in the
department's Consumer Price Index (PPI) reported Tuesday was the
largest in 17 months. For the first four months of the year and
for all of 1997, it had varied between no increase and a 0.2
percent rise. For the whole 1997, it dropped to a 1.7 percent low.
</P>
<P>
However, many of the items fueling inflation in May were viewed
as temporary, so there's little sign inflation is headed
dramatically higher either.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report today, the Federal Reserve said production
at the nation's factories, mines and utilities rose 0.5 percent,
the largest increase in six months. It was driven by a 2.8 percent
surge at utilities, particularly for electricity generation, and a
1.2 percent jump at mines, reflecting a large gain in coal
production. At factories, production edged 0.2 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
The country's industry was operating at 82.2 percent of
capacity, up slightly from 82.1 percent in April and the same as
in March and February. That level indicates little danger of
inflationary bottlenecks developing.
</P>
<P>
For the first five months of the year, inflation ran at a 1.5
percent annual rate. Excluding the volatile food and energy
sectors, the "core rate" of inflation advanced at a 2.7 percent
annual rate, compared with a 2.2 percent increase for all of last
year.
</P>
<P>
Most of the deterioration in the core rate were blamed for
price increases by tobacco companies preparing to settle
multimillion-dollar liability lawsuits. Cigarette prices rose 2.6
percent in May. They're 7.7 percent higher than at the end of
1997.
</P>
<P>
Prescription drug prices rose 1 percent in May, the largest
increase since August 1991. Medical care overall was up 0.3
percent for the month and 3.1 percent over the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
Increases also were registered for child care and nursery
school, clothing and cable television.
</P>
<P>
However, new-car prices fell 0.3 percent, the result of U.S.
manufacturers' effort to compete with imports, whose price has
been lowered by the devaluation of the Japanese yen. Car prices
are down 0.9 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The price of personal computers also fell, as did sporting
goods, home furnishings, video and audio equipment and toys, all
likely the result of the problems in Asia. Airline fares fell 2.4
percent, the second consecutive drop, after rising 8.2 percent
during the first three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, food prices jumped 0.6 percent in May, the largest
pace since October 1996. Lettuce costs soared 26.4 percent, the
result of El Nino's rains washing out California vegetable fields.
Vegetable prices overall shot up 11.9 percent, the biggest
increase in three years.
</P>
<P>
However, wholesale vegetable prices already are headed down as
farmers in the South harvest their early crops.
</P>
<P>
Energy costs increased 0.3 percent, the most since September.
Most of that came from an 0.8 percent increase in gasoline.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
