<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Upgrades Kariba Power Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Electricity Supply
Authority (ZESA) has refurnished its Kariba South Power Station
in the north at the cost of about 14 million U.S. Dollars to
improve its power generating capacity.
</P>
<P>
A senior ZESA official, James Chiuta Tuesday said the
upgrading of the turbines, which will see them last the next 30
years, will significantly improve turbine efficiency and provide
an increase in output.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when he was presenting a study paper on
the Kariba Dam at the on-going 23rd Southern African Development
Community (SADC) energy ministers meeting which focused its
discinto the sector, the Zimbabwen News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Kariba Dam is the third largest hydro-electric power
reservior in the world with a design volume of 180 billion cubic
meters.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the meeting, Edward Rugoyi of the Southern African
Power Pool (SAPP) said the SAPP will soon establish a
co-ordination centre maintain an effective organisation and
infrastructure which promotes the interest and image of SAPP
members.
</P>
<P>
He said the co-ordination centre will be a permanent and
independent entity free from the control and influence of any
power utilities.
</P>
<P>
Countries in the region get their power from an
inter-connected system through SAPP and Harare was chosen as the
location for the co-ordination centre which is obliged to monitor
the operations of the power pool transactions between operating
members, to carry out technical studies on the power pool and to
evaluate the impact of future projects on its operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
