<HEADLINE> Cambodia's Sam Rainsy Party to Go Ahead With Demonstration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Cambodian Sam Rainsy Party
announced Tuesday it will proceed to organize on Sunday a peaceful
demonstration in support of fair elections despite the
government's ban on demonstrations before the elections.
</P>
<P>
Phnom Penh municipality issued an order last weekend, which
took effect immediately, banning any demonstrations until after
the scheduled July 26 elections so as to maintain good security,
public order and a good atmosphere of neutral politics.
</P>
<P>
Municipal cabinet chief Mann Chhoeun said the suspension was in
accordance with an order from the Interior Ministry to maintain a
good atmosphere leading up to the polls.
</P>
<P>
But a statement released by Sam Rainsy Party (former Khmer
Nation Party) accused the order of violating the Constitution and
therefore illegal and unenforceable.
</P>
<P>
Party leader Sam Rainsy said the demonstration planned for June
21 "is precisely on the issue of asking for free and fair
elections and pointing out the shortcomings of the current
electoral process."
</P>
<P>
He expected 10,000 people, including those deprived of the
right to register for voting, would take part in the parade on
June 21, the day after the Friends of Cambodia group of nations
meet in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
According to National Election Committee's figures, about 4.7
million people, or 92 percent of the eligible voters, registered
during the four-week voter registration drive. 
</P>
