<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Currency Cheapest in History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU,June 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Dollar, the leading
hard currency in Mogadishu, Tuesday scratched 8,600 against the
Somali Shillings, the highest ever reached in the history.
</P>
<P>
According to dealers in Bakara market, one of the main
currency markets in the capital city, the Somali Shilling has
started loosing ground a month ago after the business communities
lost their sympathy for the faction leaders following their
failure and continuous postponement of establishing
administration in Mogadishu and reopening the air and sea ports.
</P>
<P>
Abdurahman Abdulle Sanweyneh, one of the well-known business
owners in Bakara market, said that they have observed many
business people who are changing their money into the U.S.
Dollars so that they can start new business activities elsewhere
in Africa, favorably in Kenya, Malawi and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Many Somalis are already having large businesses in Kenya
following the collapse of the former regime in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Sanweyneh said that the Somalis are unfortunately lacking
political stability which has been the basic ground for
guaranteeing the large business opportunities.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the quick rise of the U.S Dollar value is also
attributed to the withdrawal of the international aid agencies
from Mogadishu following the abduction of the 10 International
Red Cross aid workers in Mogadishu in April this year.
</P>
<P>
The aid agencies had injected a considerable amount of money
into the poor economy of Somalia in their various humanitarian
and development projects.
</P>
<P>
The high rate of the U.S. Dollar is also seriously affecting
almost all the prices of the imported goods including food,
clothes and cosmetics.
</P>
<P>
The other currencies such as Kenyan Shilling, Ethiopian Birr
and Saudi Arabian Riyal are also following the footsteps of the
U.S. Dollars by increasing about five percent each during the
past two days.
</P>
<P>
Even though the supper decentralized economy of Somalia is
lacking administration, the Somali Shillings had maintained a
stable value against the U.S. Dollars in most of the seven-year
long civil strife. The U.S. Dollar had floated between 6,500 and
7,500 Somali Shillings until very recently.
</P>
<P>
This high value for the U.S. Dollar is contrary to the
habitual depreciation of other currencies which often lose their
values against the Somali Shillings during the high tide season
of the Indian Ocean when the demand of U.S. Dollars will decrease
to the minimal since the imports will close down for the four
months between June and September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
