<HEADLINE> Mozambique May Rejoin COMESA When Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The visiting Mozambican Foreign
Minister, Leonardo Santo Simao, said here Tuesday that his
country will consider rejoining the Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) when its economy improves.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with Enoch Kavindele, the outgoing Chairman of
COMESA Council of Ministers and Zambian Minister of Commerce,
Trade and Industry, Simao said that Mozambique has nothing
against COMESA and may rejoin the organization when its economy
has picked up.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique left COMESA about two years ago due to difficulties
in subscribing to many regional organizations, the Zambia News
Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In response to Kavindele's call for Mozambique to rejoin the
19-member regional body, Simao who is on a three-day visit to
Zambia explained that during the period of national
reconstruction, Mozambique decided to withdraw membership from
some organizations that do not benefit the country immediately.
</P>
<P>
Earlier during the meeting, Kavindele asked Mozambique to
reconsider returning to COMESA at some stage due to increasing
intra-regional trade.
</P>
<P>
Kavindele said that Mozambique should rejoin COMESA
particularly because its trading capacity with other countries is
on increase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
