<HEADLINE> Israel Refuses to Extradite Hezbollah Activist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Israel on Tuesday rejected a
request to extradite a Hezbollah activist who is a German citizen
to Germany for trial, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
A representative of the State Attorney Office told Tel-Aviv
district court during a hearing that Israel wants to try in the
Jewish state Stefan Josef Smirak, who was recruited by Hezbollah,
or Party of God, to attack Israelis.
</P>
<P>
The representative noted that according to the European
Convention on Extradition, there is no obligation to extradite a
person who has already been indicted in the country where he was
arrested.
</P>
<P>
But the defense council for Smirak argued that its client can
not get a fair trial in Israel, which it said wants to hold him as
a bargaining chip for future prisoner exchange with Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
Smirak, a convert to Islam, was reportedly recruited by the
militant group Hezbollah during his visit to Lebanon between
August and November in 1997.
</P>
<P>
During this period, he was sent to a training camp in the Bekka
Valley in Lebanon, where he was taught how to use light weapons
and operate explosive devices.
</P>
<P>
Sent by Hezbollah to launch a suicide attack in Israel last
November, he was arrested on arrival at the Ben-Gurion Airport in
Tel-Aviv.
</P>
<P>
Smirak was indicted on December 25 last year on charge of
planning terror attacks in Israel.
</P>
<P>
While under the interrogation of Israeli General Security
Service, he confessed to acting against Israel and said that if
he were released, he would continue his efforts to kill Israelis.
</P>
<P>
The charge against Smirak carries a maximum penalty of life
imprisonment and the next hearing on his case is set for June
30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
