<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawian Medical College Embarks on Anti-Biotic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 16 (Xinhua)--The University of Malawi's College
of Medicine has launched a study to see if anti-biotic
bacterium can prolong the life of a tuberculosis (TB) patient who
also carries HIV, the Malawi News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Head of medicine department at the college at Blantyre's major
referral hospital, the Queen Elizabeth Central Hospital (QECH),
Martin Bouree told Malawi's daily The Nation Monday that research
in Europe and west African has shown that bacterium can prolong
the life of an HIV-positive TB patient.
</P>
<P>
Bouree has therefore been testing the bacteria treatment on
200 patients at QECH over the past 6 months to validate the
finding.
</P>
<P>
"TB cases are increasing at an alarming rate, with five new
cases reported everyday at the hospital alone and 68 countrywide,
claiming 9,000 lives annually," said Bouree.
</P>
<P>
"Three out of four TB patients at QECH are also HIV-positive,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Malawi has one of the highest TB and HIV/AIDS rates in the
southern Africa region largely attributed to the rampant poverty
and scanty information on the killer disease among the majority
rural people. Ninety percent of Malawi's population of 11 million
live in rural areas and 60 percent live below the poverty line
and are illiterate.
</P>
<P>
"We have two groups. One group takes one tablet of bacterium
for each patient and the other group two tablets for each
patient. We want to see if the medicine can prolong the life of
these patients who also carry the AIDS virus," said Bouree,
adding that this is also in addition to the usual TB treatment
they receive.
</P>
<P>
He said that the college is also studying how long a patient
coughs before TB is diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
This particular research, he said, will also help traditional
healers to know how long they should keep patients in their
places who "are coughing and may carry the TB germ."
</P>
<P>
He said at the moment 800 traditional healers drawn
countrywide on a pilot basis are being taught on this new
development so that "they do not keep patients for too long at
their places byt are sent to the hospitals in good time for
immediate diagnosis."
</P>
<P>
Tb and AIDS which are mostly going together now are among the
highest killer diseases in this small southern African state.

NNNN
01:32 01:33 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
