<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, U.S. Making Headway on Third </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Israel and the United States
have made progress in their contacts over the scope of Israel's
third further withdrawal from the West Bank, Israel Radio reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A senior source was quoted as saying that the headway was made
in the last few days in intensive contacts between Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross.
</P>
<P>
The radio did not elaborate what progress was actually made.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli President Ezer Weizman will meet later
Tuesday with U.S. Ambassador Edward Walker to get a briefing on
the status of the ongoing Israeli-U.S. negotiations which are now
focusing on the size of the third redeployment.
</P>
<P>
The report came a day after the U.S. State Department
vigorously denied Israel and the Palestinians are on the verge of
a redeployment agreement.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said Monday that Israel
and the Palestinians still disagree on the issue, and any reports
suggesting that an agreement has been reached totally wrong.
</P>
<P>
Although Israel has never publicly adopted the U.S. proposal
for a 13 percent withdrawal in the second redeployment, it seemed
the dispute is over as Netanyahu is ready to accept it. But a new
dispute over the third redeployment has surfaced as Netanyahu is
trying to cancel or minimize the scope of the last redeployment.
</P>
<P>
There are sharp differences within the so-called "kitchen
cabinet," created by Netanyahu to deal with core security matters,
over how to continue the negotiations with the U.S., the radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, a leading dove within the
Cabinet, has pressed Netanyahu to speed up the redeployment
decision in order to move ahead to the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
But the hawkish National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon
insisted that Israel should stand firm to safeguard its vital
security interests. He believes that any pullback exceeding 9
percent will compromise the country's security.
</P>
<P>
A major far-rightist coalition party, National Religious Party
(NRP), has warned Netanyahu against carrying out a significant
pullback, or it would topple the government.
</P>
<P>
To allay concerns of his far-rightist partners, Netanyahu has
been seeking a "total package" on combining the second and third
redeployments in the West Bank. Under the package, Israel accepts
the 13 percent pullback proposal on condition that the third
redeployment will be only 2 percent and the final-status talks
should be immediately started.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side has flatly rejected the idea of another 2
percent withdrawal in the third redeployment, while Washington has
also reportedly refused to commit itself to this figure.
</P>
<P>
Israeli newspaper Haaretz quoted government sources as saying
Tuesday that as part of the redeployment package, Israel wants
the U.S. to provide a letter of assurance making clear that
Washington will oppose any unilateral declaration of Palestinian
statehood until the peace process is completed. In return, Israel
will agree to forgo any construction of new settlements.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has vowed that on May 5 of
next year, he will declare an independent Palestinian state
whether progress in the peace process will be made or not.
</P>
<P>
Observers believed that by seeking the U.S. assurance, Israel
hopes to make sure that its best card -- namely, Israeli
recognition of Palestinian statehood -- is not discarded by
premature U.S. recognition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
