<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Insects Helpful in Criminal Investigation: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A South African medical
expert has found that insects can be helpful to police in
establishing the time of death of victims of crime.
</P>
<P>
Theunis Van der Linde, forensic entomologist at the University
of the Orange Free State, used his expertise to help police
investigate nearly 100 cases of unnatural death over the last
five years, The Citizen newspaper Tuesday quoted a statement by
the Medical Research Council (MRC) of South Africa as saying.
</P>
<P>
Forensic entomology, which analyses insects found on
decomposing bodies, is often the only scientifically reliable
method to determine the time of death when a body is found in an
advanced state of decomposition.
</P>
<P>
"Insects are always the first to discover the body, sometimes
within minutes after the person had died, and they always arrive
in particular pattern," Van der Linde was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said blowflies arrived first, followed by beetles and ants
when the body was in a more decomposed state. Predators also
visited the body to feed on larvae.
</P>
<P>
A final group, known as "the tourists" (cockroaches,
butterflies and moths), simply used the environment of the
</P>
<P>
body to hide, Van der Linde said.
</P>
<P>
The research, contained in the MRC's latest annual report, is
one of several projects on crime prevention supported by the MRC
as part of a national initiative against crime undertaken by the
Department of Arts, Culture, Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
The MRC said that Van der Linde had established a model using
dead animals to determine the pattern of insects visiting
carcasses. The carcasses were burnt, frozen, or simply left to
the elements in both winter and summer trial.
</P>
<P>
Van der Linde also studied carcasses which had been left in
shady and sunny position, immersed in water, or hanging, the MRC
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
