<HEADLINE> Arafat Starts Consultations on Cabinet Reshuffle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat on Tuesday started consulations in
Gaza with other political factions on his imminent cabinet
reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
According to East Jerusalem-based Palestinian press service
JMCC, Arafat has met with leaders of the Palestinian Legislative
Council (PLC) on Monday to secure a 10-day delay of a
no-confidence vote against his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Abu Ala, speaker of the legislature, said during the meeting
that the new cabinet should carry out administration reforms as
demanded by the lawmakers. The incumbent cabinet is riddled with
charges from mismanagement to corruption.
</P>
<P>
The speaker said the new cabinet should be responsible for all
phases of the interim agreement, prepare for national
independence, build strong national institutions and do everything
possible to meet the requirements of the people and increase their
living standards.
</P>
<P>
He and other PLC leaders also gave their suggestions on the
structure of the new government, but no details in this regard
were disclosed.
</P>
<P>
All other Palestinian factions, including the Islamic
Resistance Movement (Hamas) and Islamic Jihad, expressed their
welcome to Arafat's ongoing consultations on cabinet reshuffle,
saying such steps are conducive to the national reconciliations.
</P>
<P>
But a PNA source said in Gaza that because Hamas spiritual
leader Sheikh Ahmed Yassin has not returned to Gaza from a
fund-raising tour of regional Arab countries, Arafat's talks with
him have been postponed.
</P>
<P>
Other leaders of Hamas and Islamic Jihad said earlier that
they will not join the new government headed by Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The consultations will last for four days. After that, Arafat
would present the list of his new government to the legislative
body.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Arafat plans to fire Faisal Husseini,
minister for Jerusalem affairs, and replace him with Omar Khatib,
the PNA representative in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Arafat is not happy with Husseini's
spending of donations he received abroad and did not hand over to
the PNA to be included in its budget.
</P>
<P>
Husseini refused to comment on this report in East Jerusalem on
Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Milosevic Ready to Talk With Kosovo Albanians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic agreed on Tuesday to resume talks with a moderate leader
of Kosovo's ethnic Albanians in an effort to defuse the crisis in
the southern Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached after his talks with Russian
President Boris Yeltsin, Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov and
other Russian leaders in the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic, who arrived here Monday night on a brief working
visit, said Belgrade is ready to resume talks with Ibrahim Rugova,
a political leader of Kosovo's Albanians, and not with the Kosovo
Liberation Army, the armed wing of the Kosovo independence
movement.
</P>
<P>
More than 250 people have died in clashes between government
forces and the KLA in the region where ethnic Albanians, who
account for 90 percent of the population, are demanding
independence from the Yugoslav Republic of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
"I see no reason to conduct negotiations with terrorists,"
Milosevic told reporters, referring to the KLA.
</P>
<P>
He denied that his decision to find a peaceful solution to the
conflict was a result of pressure from NATO air exercises over
neighboring Albania and Macedonia that began Monday.
</P>
<P>
In televised comments after his talks with Milosevic, Yeltsin
said "the most important thing is that Milosevic agreed to sit at
the negotiating table with the Kosovo Albanians".
</P>
<P>
According to a joint statement, read by Primakov, talks on all
issues concerning Kosovo, including possible forms of an
autonomous status for the area, will be held uninterruptedly in
accordance with a schedule approved by the sides and in line with
international standards, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reaffirmed the need to preserve Yugoslavia's
territorial integrity and condemned "any manifestations of
terrorism, separatism and armed actions affecting the civilian
population," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The document said that full freedom of movement will be ensured
throughout Kosovo as a confidence-building measure.
</P>
<P>
It also guaranteed employees of the International Committee of
the Red Cross and the Office of the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees free access to Yugoslav areas and unhindered delivery of
humanitarian aid to the regions.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that Yugoslav government forces will reduce
their presence in Kosovo as terrorist activity diminishes.
</P>
<P>
"The ball is now mainly in the court of Kosovo's Albanians,"
Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic, for his part, welcomed "Russia's clearly expressed
stand" against sanctions on Yugoslavia and in favor of restoring
Yugoslavia's membership in international organizations."
</P>
<P>
Belgrade is ready to begin talks with the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe on the establishment of an OSCE
mission in Kosovo and reinstating Yugoslavia within the
organization.
</P>
<P>
The statement gave a realistic opportunity to settle the
situation in Kosovo, Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after his talks with Milosevic, Yeltsin called U.S.
President Bill Clinton and briefed him on the talks with
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
Clinton expressed satisfaction at the agreements reached with
the Yugoslav leadership, especially its readiness to immediately
resume negotiations with the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, Yeltsin's
press service said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also agreed that the U.S. secretary of state
and the Russian foreign minister will continue consultations on
the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic is scheduled to leave here for home late Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
