<HEADLINE> Iraq Hails New Agreement With U.N. Inspectors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's Deputy Prime Minister Tareq
Aziz said on Tuesday that the agreement reached with
U.N. inspectors recently represented "a major turning-point" in
the relationship between the two parties.
</P>
<P>
Aziz made the remarks following the opening ceremony of
Egyptian Products Fair in Baghdad which was organized by 121
Egyptian companies.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and the U.N. Special Commission on disarmament in Iraq,
known as UNSCOM, reached the agreement on the program of work in
the next two months during the commission chief Richard Butler's
recent five-day visit to Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Butler told a press conference before leaving Baghdad on Sunday
that if Iraq cooperates fully and give access to important
documents and materials, he will begin to prepare a report which
will lead to the lifting of trade embargo imposed on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Aziz described the agreement was "a good outcome that
represents the willingness of the best people, world public
opinion and all people who call for an end to the embargo."
</P>
<P>
The relationship between Baghdad and the UNSCOM has hardly had
a good time as U.N. inspectors accused Baghdad of refusing to
cooperate. A crisis which arose early this year almost triggered a
war.
</P>
<P>
Aziz also called for an early lifting of the U.N. sanctions
imposed on Iraq in 1990 after its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions can only be lifted when UNSCOM verifies that
Iraq is free of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
On Iraq's relations with Arab countries, Aziz said Iraq "has a
sincere willingness to develop relations" with Arab states, and
that the willingness has become a reality "because Iraqi market
has been receiving many Egyptian goods and has room for more."
</P>
<P>
Aziz stressed that Iraq believed seriously in joint Arab work
and cooperation, elaborating that joint work with Egypt has always
been one of the priorities in the approach of the Iraqi leadership.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
