<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Underscores Need of Protecting Free Shipping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- In its reaction to Turkey's search
of a Maltese-flagged vessel, Cyprus on Tuesday undercored the need
for protecting the freedom of international shipping.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Customs authorities intercepted and searched a
Maltese-flagged vessel in the Dardanelles, suspected of carrying
components of Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles to
Cyprus. The vessel was released eight hours later after it was
found that the cargo was destined for Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on this incident, Cypriot Government spokesman
Christos Stylianides said that even Cyprus was not involved in
this case because the ship was neither registered under the Cyprus
flag and nor destined for Cyprus, the Cypriot government must
underline its support for free shipping.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that to protect the freedom of shipping, all
international conventions and agreements on shipping should be
implemented.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus clinched a deal with Russia in January 1997 to buy S-300
missiles worth 400 million U.S. dollars in order to increase its
defense capability.
</P>
<P>
The deal, however, angered Turkey and the Turkish Cypriots
living in the northern part of the divided island, who vowed to
take all possible means to prevent the deployment of the missiles.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of an abortive coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Greece, Cyprus' strong supporter, announced last week that the
delivery of the S-300 missiles, scheduled for mid-August, would be
delayed until November.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has said that it can cancel the deployment of S-300
defense system only if considerable progress is made toward a
comprehensive Cyprus settlement or an agreement for the island's
demilitarization is reached. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
