<HEADLINE> Arab League to Consider Ending Embargo on Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) may join the
African countries in an effort to bring the U.N.-imposed embargo
against Libya to a quick end, a senior AL official implied Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
AL Assistant Secretary General Zakariya Ismail said Arab
foreign ministers will consider swift steps toward doing away with
the embargo in their next regular meeting in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed a resolution adopted by the summit of Organization
of African Unity (OAU) last week in Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso, to
conditionally lift sanctions against Libya.
</P>
<P>
The northern African country has been under an air, arms and
diplomatic embargo since 1992 after Tripoli refused to hand over
two Libyans suspected of involvement in blowing up a Pan-Am
airliner in 1988 over Lockerbie, Scotland, killing 270 people, to
stand trial in the U.S. or Britain.
</P>
<P>
Tripoli argued the two have no chance of getting a fair trial
in the two countries, and insisted that they be tried in a neutral
country or by the International Court of Justice in the Hague. The
stance is backed by families of the victims but shrugged off by
both the U.S. and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The OAU resolution stipulates that as of September 1, the
African states will not abide by the embargo imposed on Libya if
the West continues to refuse that the two Libyans stand trial in a
neutral country.
</P>
<P>
Nine Arab countries took part in the OAU summit, whose
resolution will "influence the Arab decision-making," Ismail
pointed out, implying the 22-member AL may follow suit.
</P>
<P>
"It has been proven since the ruling of the International Court
of Justice that it is within its jurisdiction to examine the
Lockerbie issue, that sanctions imposed on Libya should be lifted
since they have no legal grounds and only express a political
stance," Ismail said.
</P>
<P>
AL Secretary General Esmat Abdel Meguid flew to London Sunday
on a four-day visit in which he would discuss the Libyan-West
stand-off with British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook.
</P>
<P>
Libya has reportedly suffered up to 23.56 billion U.S. dollars
in losses since the sanctions began six years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0040 </DOCNO>
