<HEADLINE> Southern Africa Woos Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano said Tuesday that foreign investment is welcome in
Mozambique and southern Africa, where joint ventures are of great
significance to the success of social and economic policies.
</P>
<P>
"The governments of southern African countries are carrying
out macro-economic policies aimed at regaining the confidence of
the international community which had been weakened by
instability and armed conflicts in the past," said Chissano in
his opening speech at the Southern Africa Investors Forum.
</P>
<P>
According to the president, southern Africa is now no longer
a region of high risks, but one of peaceful co-existence and
cooperation, and one committed to progress and development.
</P>
<P>
So long as the economies are liberalized, investment
encouraged and infrastructure network restored, the economic
potentials in the region will be fully explored, Chissano noted.
</P>
<P>
He called for concerted efforts by governments and
entrepreneurs to achieve economic prosperity in the southern
African region so as to rival with other emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
The president also briefed the forum on some big projects
Mozambique is now undertaking, such as the Maputo Development
Corridor and the Libombos development initiative involving
Mozambique, South Africa and Swaziland, adding that investors in
the development program of Zambeze Valley will enjoy free tariff
for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
The forum to be ended Friday has drawn about 500 people
from over 20 countries in southern Africa, Europe and Asia.
</P>
