<HEADLINE> Arab Investments in Arab Countries Valued at 1.5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Arab investments in projects
in Arab countries last year were estimated at 1.5 billion
U.S. dollars, said an economic report published here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwait-based Arab Institution for Investment Insurance
indicated in the report that the figure could reach 2 billion
dollars once complete information about investments have been
gathered.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Egypt ranks first among host Arab
countries of Arab investments, with an estimated value of 532
million dollars, followed by Syria, 328 million dollars and
Lebanon, 312 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The largest Arab investor is Saudi Arabia, followed by the
United Arab Emirates, Kuwait, Qatar, Lebanon, and Libya, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Saudi investments made up 56 percent of the total Arab
investments in Egypt, 52 percent in Yemen, 47 percent in Sudan, 40
percent in Oman, 39 percent in Lebanon and 33 percent in Tunis.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti investments have been estimated to account for 23
percent of the total Arab investments in Tunis, 21 percent in
Egypt, 19 percent in Lebanon and Syria, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
