<HEADLINE> Chamonix to Hold First World Tourism Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Chamonix, a French resort bordering
Geneva of Switzerland, will hold the first World Tourism Summit on
December 1-3, 1999, the organizing committee announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Chamonix provides visitors with a view to the highest summit in
Europe, the Mont-Blanc (4807 meters), which is the third most
visited natural site in the world.
</P>
<P>
The World Tourism Summit is the missing link and is a major
challenge, said Michel Charlet, mayor of Chamonix.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, internationally recognized experts will
debate the implications of tourism on long term development, a
concept widely accepted but whose execution is often problematic.
</P>
<P>
In the coming years, other themes will be on the agenda: the
effects of tourism on economic growth, employment, health,
alimentary habits, national cultural identities, and transport.
</P>
<P>
Today, tourism represents the biggest single factor of travel
in the world, with 550 million people travelling to a multitude of
destinations.
</P>
<P>
Tourism was originally limited to the industrialized nations
but over the past two decades it has become a world-wide
phenomenon with competition exacerbated by the dawn of new
technology and means of communication.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
