<HEADLINE> Cyprus: Cooperation With Greece Key to Counter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus Defense Minister Yiannakis
Omirou Tuesday stressed the importance of military cooperation
with Greece in the context of "Turkish expansionism."
</P>
<P>
Omirou made the remarks in a statement issued after four Greek
F-16 fighters landed at Andreas Papandreou air base near the
western coastal town of Paphos, Cyprus News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said the landing of the aircraft conveys a specific
political message: that the military cooperation "will develop as
long as there is Turkish expansionism."
</P>
<P>
It also proved the air base was ready for use, he said, adding
Greek military officers were briefed on and shown around the base.
</P>
<P>
The air base, constructed under the 1993 joint defense pact
between Cypriot and Greek governments, is to be used by Greek Air
Force planes. It has been completed in January.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash has warned against
the opening of the airbase to the Greek fighters, saying that the
Turkish Air Force will break the wings of the Greek warplanes if
they land at the base.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey
landed its troops and took over the northern third of the island
in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared "Turkish Republic
of Northern Cyprus" in 1983 in the north, which is recognized only
by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has kept a 35,000-strong armed forces in northern Cyprus.
</P>
</TEXT>
