<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Gov't Report Regards Alcohol as Dangerous </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A French government report published
on Tuesday said that alcohol is as dangerous as the most harmful
drugs such as heroin and cocaine.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for the government to put alcohol among
the top dangerous substances for human consumption and it could
trigger protests from the country's powerful wine and beer
producers.
</P>
<P>
French State Minister in charge of public health Bernard
Kouchner presented the report written by a group of experts to the
Senate, which was debating policy to reduce the risk of drug
addiction.
</P>
<P>
"Scientific facts show that there is no difference in causing
neurotoxicity between alcohol and cocaine," said the report, which
was written under Professor Pierre-Bernard Roques of the National
Council of Scientific Research (CNRS).
</P>
<P>
It used several parameters to measure the degree of harmfulness
of drugs, tobacco and alcohol, such as psychological and psychic
dependence of their addicts, their neuro-toxicity rates, their
capability to cause social dangers, and the existence or no of
substitutes for them.
</P>
<P>
"The state of depression, the compulsive and obsessional
troubles, the anti-social personalities, and anxiety are found
with very high rates among the subjects relying on heroin,
alcohol, and cocaine," it said.
</P>
<P>
The report regarded tobacco as more dangerous than cannabis but
less so than alcohol, heroin and cocaine.
</P>
<P>
More than one in 10 women and more than one in four men in
France have the habit of excessive drinking, according to former
Minister of Health Herve Gaymard.
</P>
<P>
Each year in France, 52,000 people were killed because of
reasons linked directly or indirectly with alcohol and 4,000
killed in driving in drunkenness.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
