<HEADLINE> 167 Turkish Officers Sacked for Islamic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- In a show of its resolve to crack
down on Islamic fundamentalism, the Turkish army sacked 167
servicemen Tuesday for suspected involvement in radical activities.
</P>
<P>
The order was issued by the Supreme Military Council (SMC) at a
meeting co-chaired by Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz and Chief of
General Staff Ismail Hakki Karadayi.
</P>
<P>
Most of the sacked personnel, 58 officers and 109
non-commissioned officers, had allegedly been involved in
fundamentalist activities, the Anatolia News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The council's decision is final and cannot be challenged at the
courts, which have no jurisdiction over the matter.
</P>
<P>
Turkish military, which regards itself as protector of the
country's secular system, sacks some military officers relating to
fundamentalist groups every year.
</P>
<P>
At the Tuesday meeting, Karadayi once again stressed the
importance of fighting fundamentalism in the country. He
complained of the government's inaction in taking tough measures
against those religious extremists, who want to establish an
Islamic state.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued following the meeting said that the
participants also discussed "foreign threats against Turkey."
</P>
<P>
The SMC meeting is usually called in August and December each
year. Tuesday's meeting, the first in this year, was moved up due
to the increasing concern of the military over the rapidly
spreading fundamentalist activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
