<HEADLINE> Three GCC States Agree to Cut Oil Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Three of the six members of
the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) agreed on Tuesday in Saudi
capital Riyadh to cut their oil output by a total of 170,000
barrels per day (bpd).
</P>
<P>
This is the latest of a string of moves taken by oil producers
to trim crude supply in order to shore up the sagging oil prices
on the world market.
</P>
<P>
GCC Assistant Secretary General for Economic Affairs Abdullah
Al-Khleifi said at the one-day meeting of GCC oil ministers
Tuesday that Kuwait agreed to slash its output by 75,000 bpd, the
United Arab Emirates by 75,000 bpd and Oman by 20,000 bpd.
</P>
<P>
According to the Kuwait News Agency, Al-Khleifi said that the
reduction of oil production would start on July 1 and last until
the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, which holds most of the Arab crude reserves, with
a proven total of 261.5 billion barrels, had already promised in
an agreement on June 4 with Mexico and Venezuela to cut its output
by 225,000 bpd.
</P>
<P>
GCC oil ministers convened their 21st session at a time when
the oil prices still languished between 12 and 14 U.S. dollars per
barrel despite output cuts, far below the reference price of 21
dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
The ministers of Bahrain, Oman, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, the
United Arab Emirates and Qatar, held three rounds of talks in the
day to discuss the world market situation and ways to bolster the
oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The GCC oil producers, whose economy depends heavily on oil
earnings, have taken a hard hit in the current oil price slump
resulting from oversupply and flagging demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
