<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Intentionally Lets Yen down: U.S. Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Some advisers of U.S. President
Bill Clinton have said that Japan is letting its currency down so
that its goods would be less expensive in the United States and
Washington has little leverage remaining over Tokyo, the New York
Times said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The conclusion was reached after recent internal debates
within the Clinton administration, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The purposes of the Japanese hidden strategy to let a sharp
fall of the yen is to make it nearly impossible for other
Asian nations to export more goods into Japan while Japanese
goods could push out products that other ailing Asian nations
are trying to export to the United States and Europe,
particularly South Korean cars, steel and semiconductors.
</P>
<P>
"What is happening in Japan is hitting all of its neighbors
-- Korea, Thailand -- and it is triggering a huge amount of
instability around the world," Charlene Barshefsky was quoted by
the newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Barshefsky, a veteran of five years of trade war with Japan,
told the New York Times that the United States would put
pressure on Japan to reform its economy. But she conceded the
threat to block Japanese goods such as cars and computer chip
from U.S. shores would probably accentuate Japan's troubles if
used to compel Tokyo to speed up economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
Administration officials in private have long referred to
Japan as "the last firewall" of the Asian crisis, and contended
that if that wall were breached, it was only a matter of time
before Asia's trouble leaped the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
It is an unproven thesis, but clearly investors harbor the
same worry, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin has repeatedly argued
that the Asian crisis poses a rising threat to the United
States. However, the recent run on the yen may have been helped,
intentionally or not, by Rubin, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Rubin told Congress that he had not backed away
from his mantra that "a strong dollar is in the interest of the
United States." A strong dollar benefits American companies
by making it possible for them to snap up assets across Asia at
fire sale prices, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Investors have interpreted those comments as a license to
sell the yen, without fear that the United States would join
Japan in an effort to bolster the yen. "They are probably
reading him correctly," the newspaper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
