<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Milosevic's Offer Not Enough </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said Tuesday that Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic had failed to meet most of the U.S. demands despite his
promise to resume talks with the Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at Congress, Albright said there was some progress in
Milsoevic's meeting in Moscow with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin, but Milosevic did not pledge to halt "torching the
various populations" in the province.
</P>
<P>
Albright also urged Belgrade to withdraw all its troops from
the Serbian province, criticizing the Yugoslav president for
conditioning any pullback of Serbian forces on Albanian extremists
halting their attacks.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that "all options are open," including military
options, and that a U.S. warning under the Bush administration in
1992 of unilateral U.S. action "is still valid."
</P>
<P>
"NATO leaders have not ruled out the use of force," she said.
"Contingency planning is under way," although the United States
would far prefer a diplomatic settlement of the crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The key U.S. demands, endorsed Friday at a foreign ministers
meeting in London by Russia and six other U.S. allies, are a
cease-fire, a pullback of Serb forces, resumption of negotiations
with Albanian leaders, a monitoring system and return of refugees
to their homes.
</P>
<P>
While the allies are united in their demands, there is some
disagreement on how to proceed. Russia, for instance, dissented
from the decision Friday to cut off Yugoslav commercial flights.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration believes that a new U.N. Security
Council resolution is not required to take military action while
Britain is pushing for such a resolution which could be vetoed by
Russia in the Security Council. 
</P>
