<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Business Leaders: Engaging China, Critical </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- American business leaders
kicked off a nationwide campaign here Tuesday to increase
understanding of trade issues, particularly the importance of
maintaining normal trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
The campaign called "Go Trade: Compete to Win" was sponsored by
the Business Roundtable (BRT), which voices strong support for the
renewal of China's most favored nation (MFN) trading status, a
controversial issue in Congress.
</P>
<P>
"Trade is the fuel of our economy. International trade and
investment are, more than ever, critical for the well-being of the
United States, its companies and its workers," BRT Chairman Donald
V. Fites told a press conference on the Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
A 30-second television spot was shown and later distributed at
the press conference, featuring an American girl and a Chinese boy
playing together. The spot script goes, "It's not child's play.
Learning to share is serious business."
</P>
<P>
Joseph T. Gorman, chairman of the BRT's Task Force on
International Trade and Investment, said that the renewal of
China's MFN is the key to continued constructive engagement with
China because it will advance important U.S. national security,
foreign policy and economic interests.
</P>
<P>
"MFN, or non-discriminatory treatment of trading partners, is
the norm in international trade -- not a privilege or `favor'
accorded to friendly nations," Gorman said.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton recommended to Congress on June 3 that
China's MFN be extended for another year, a policy pursued by his
predecessors since 1980. Some congressional critics have raised
their voices of opposition before the president flies to visit
China later this month.
</P>
<P>
"MFN not only supports hundreds of thousands of U.S. jobs
created by exports, but also supports U.S. companies operating in
China that contribute to the continued expansion of economic,
political and social reform in that country," Gorman noted.
</P>
<P>
The trade between China and the U.S. has grown at an annual
rate of over 18 percent since 1979. China has become the U.S.'
fourth largest trading partner while the U.S. is China's second
largest. Direct exports to China creates more than 300,000 job
opportunities in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of Commerce William Daley joined the business leaders
at the press conference, reaffirming that the U.S.-China relations
would be the most important bilateral ties in the world in the
years to come, and normal trade status should be accorded to
China.
</P>
<P>
Congressman David Dreier shared the belief that the U.S. should
follow a "Double Win" China policy. He noted that the two
countries disagree on many issues, however, the most important
thing is to find the best way to address them.
</P>
<P>
He believed that President Clinton's upcoming visit to China
and the renewal of China's MFN would contribute to better
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Congressman Jim Kolbe applauded the BRT's efforts to renew
China's MFN, saying that "America's relationship with China
presents the most complex and significant foreign policy challenge
we face."
</P>
<P>
He was concerned about the lack of understanding among the
American people, quoting a recent poll which showed that 62
percent of the public had no knowledge of international trade and
75 percent did not even know the position of their Congressional
representatives on trade.
</P>
<P>
"This lack of knowledge plays right into the hands of the
protectionists who try to protect their narrow economic interests
at the expense of the American consumer," Kolbe said, warning
"such protectionism often results in higher prices and
lower-quality goods."
</P>
<P>
Congressman Bob Matsui also stressed the importance of
maintaining normal trade relations with China, pointing to the
significant role it played in the Asian financial crisis and the
tension in South Asia following nuclear tests by India and
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
China is trying to maintain good relations with its neighboring
countries and rejecting expansionism, and if this could be
ignored, new cold war would prevail in the next century, Matsui
warned.
</P>
<P>
The voice in favor of China's MFN was made heard before the
House Ways and Means Committee holds a hearing on the matter
Wednesday. Congress has 90 days to respond to the president's
decision.
</P>
<P>
The BRT, established in 1972, is an association of chief
executive officers who examine public issues that affect the
economy and develop positions. It groups some 200 business leaders
in all fields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
