<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drought Most Linked With Desertification: WMO Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Of many climatic events, drought is
perhaps the one that is most linked with desertification, said
Secretary-General of the World Meteorological Organization (WMO)
Godwin Obasi here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The 1997-1998 El Nino, which has now entered its decaying
phase, resulted in serious drought situations in parts of South
America, Africa, Asia, Australia, New Zealand and North America,"
said Obasi in his message marking the fourth World Day to Combat
Desertification and Drought.
</P>
<P>
"These extreme weather events had an adverse impact on economic
sectors such as agriculture, fisheries, forestry, insurance and on
human health," the WMO head said.
</P>
<P>
As a member of the U.N. Inter-Agency Task Force on El Nino,
Obasi said that his organization is collaborating closely with
other U.N. bodies and agencies to develop a strategy for the
prevention, mitigation and rehabilitation of the damages caused by
this episode.
</P>
<P>
He said that desertification and drought pose major problems
for millions of people spread across many continents of the world.
</P>
<P>
Obasi called on the international community "to extend their
full cooperation and to provide the necessary information" to the
second Conference of the Parties to the U.N. Convention to Combat
Desertification, scheduled from November 30 to December 11 in
Dakar, Senegal.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays, drylands are inhabited by approximately 2.0 billion
people globally, representing about 40 percent of the world's
population.
</P>
<P>
About 54 million square kilometers, or 40 percent of the land
area of the world, can be classified as drylands, according to the
WMO.
</P>
<P>
In Africa, almost three-quarters of the agricultural drylands
are already degraded and the region is prone to frequent and
severe droughts.
</P>
<P>
In Asia, vast regions of the 1.7 billion hectares of drylands
are threatened by desertification.
</P>
<P>
Though better known for their rainforests, Latin America and
the Caribbean are actually about one-quarter desert and drylands.
In the Americas and the Caribbean, 178 million people live and
work in these drylands and therefore face the risk of
desertification and drought.
</P>
<P>
Much of the Northern Mediterranean region is semi-arid and is
subject to seasonal droughts and high rainfall variability.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
