<HEADLINE> Six Russian Satellites Enter Planned Orbit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Six Russian Kosmos satellites
launched on Tuesday reached the projected orbit and are
functioning properly, the Russian Strategic Rocket Force stated on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But the Interfax news agency quoted another military source as
saying that the first and second stages of the Tsiklon-3 launcher
fired as required, but the booster's second pulse was mistimed.
</P>
<P>
Instead of a circular orbit at an altitude of 1,400 kilometers,
the satellites are flying in an elliptical one with an apogee of
1,900 kilometers and a perigee of 1,300 kilometers, the source
said.
</P>
<P>
Both sources agreed that the six communication satellites would
operate properly for the Main Intelligence Board of the General
Staff.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Wednesday, it was reported that the six satellites
failed to reach the desired orbit, but could still be used.
</P>
<P>
The Tsiklon-3 light booster which launched the satellites was
built at the Yuzhnoye design bureau in Ukraine and based on the
R-36 ballistic missiles, the report said. 
</P>
