<HEADLINE> India Misleading World opinion by Offering Talks: Pak Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Wednesday accused India
of misleading the world community by offering bilateral talks to
Pakistan "as is evident from its double standards on the core
issue of Kashmir which lies unsettled for the last fifty years
despite the UN resolutions."
</P>
<P>
"It's a wrong impression that India first made offer of
bilateral talks to Pakistan on June 22 rather it's Pakistan which
first offered India for talks in Islamabad on June 20 by calling
Indian High Commissioner to the Foreign Office on June 11," said
Foreign Office Spokesman Tariq Altaf in an interview with Pakistan
Television telecast Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
"India instead of responding to Pakistan's initiative of
offering talks went on to announce its own offer of talks for June
22 through the world media unilaterally, thus giving a false
impression to the international community that it wanted to talk
to Pakistan on all issues," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said, India's double speaking can be judged from the fact
that on the one hand it offers bilateral talks to Pakistan on all
matters including Kashmir but on the other its leaders and
diplomats openly speak at local and international fora that
Kashmir is India's integral part.
</P>
<P>
"It seems that India is not serious in holding talks with
Pakistan at this moment and wanted to delay the matter at least
till the SAARC summit to be held at the end of next month where
the two Prime Ministers are likely to meet," the spokesman said.
The 10th summit of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) is scheduled to take place in Colombo, Sri
Lanka late July.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also called upon the international community to
come forward and help resolve the Kashmir issue as it poses a
serious threat to peace in this region.
</P>
<P>
After the nuclear explosions by India and Pakistan, the world
community now strongly feels to resolve the Kashmir issue and has
put it as first priority agenda, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, he said, will welcome any initiative from the world
community to help resolve the Kashmir issue which is the root
cause of tension between India and Pakistan, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
