<HEADLINE> SADC Members Urged to Ratify Energy Protocol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Failure by some member states to
ratify Southern African Development Community (SADC) energy
protocol is hindering plans to boost energy provision in the
region, a regional official said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
SADC energy coordinator Henrique Da Silva said the secretariat
was concerned that some member states were taking longer time
than expected to ratify the energy protocol.
</P>
<P>
He was addressing delegates from 14 member countries attending
the 23rd SADC Energy Officials and Ministers meeting.
</P>
<P>
If ratified by all member states, the protocol would see the
subsequent establishment of an energy commission along with the
replacement of the Technical and Administrative Unit by a
Technical Unit.
</P>
<P>
"Reminders were sent through the proper channels in order to
speed up this process in those countries," Da Silva said. "We
have not received enough response from some member states and we
are still short of quorum for the protocol to become effective."
</P>
<P>
However, he did not mention the member countries that still
have to ratify the protocol.
</P>
<P>
SADC countries operate under an interconnected power system
through the Southern African Power Pool (SAPP).
</P>
<P>
Da Silva said there was an urgent need for member countries to
distinguish between bilateral and regional activities to ensure
that proper procedures were followed in the implementation of
regional ones.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's Transport and Energy Secretary Paul Kodzwa stressed
that southern African countries should focus their objectives on
regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The meeting aims to review regional power policies and
discussing ways through which investment can be increased in the
energy generation sectors in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
