<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A ranking official of the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) Wednesday
appealed to Islamic countries for more financial assistance to
refugee-relief programs.
</P>
<P>
The chief of mission of the UNHCR in Kuwait, Moustafa Omar,
called on the Muslim world to help overcome his organization's
financial difficulties that could jeopardize the protection and
assistance of the world's refugees.
</P>
<P>
This is part of an urgent global campaign, which is also the
first ever staged by the UNHCR, to raise funds for its 1998
operations that cover almost 22 million refugees across the world.
</P>
<P>
Omar told a press conference here that the UNHCR budget is
financed by governments, non-governmental organizations,
individual and corporate donations. But the donations this year
covered only half the budget of 1.1 billion U.S. dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed regret that Islamic countries are not represented
as major donors, though the majority of refugees in the world are
Muslims.
</P>
<P>
There have been contacts between the UNHCR and several Gulf
Arab countries, and some of them are likely to make contributions,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Omar said that the shortage in financing will affect several
refugee programs including repatriation projects in Afghanistan,
Angola, Liberia and the Great Lakes region in Africa. 
</P>
