<HEADLINE> Chinese, British Police Cooperate In Solving Kidnapping Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and British police
cooperated recently in stopping a major kidnapping, freeing five
Chinese hostages in the process.
</P>
<P>
On June 7, police in the east China province of Fujian were
informed that a man named Liu Dafu, from the city of Fuqing, had
been kidnapped in London and that the kidnappers had called Liu's
family from London, asking for 250,000 yuan (about 31,000 U.S.
dollars) in ransom money.
</P>
<P>
The kidnappers told Liu's family to get the money ready and
that someone would come to collect it.
</P>
<P>
The police in Fujian immediately contacted police in London,
who sent three officers to China on June 11 to help with the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
On June 15, police in London arrested over 50 people suspected
of being involved with the case, while Chinese police arrested the
person who came to collect the ransom money in the city of
Changle, close to Fuqing.
</P>
<P>
Chinese and British police had cooperated previously in a
kidnapping case in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
