<HEADLINE> Aziz Meets Russian Envoy on Weapons Inspections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq
Aziz met here Wednesday with Russian presidential envoy Viktor
Posuvalyuk to review the latest developments in the U.N. weapons
inspections, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Posuvalyuk, also Russia's deputy foreign minister, arrived here
Tuesday for talks with Iraqi officials on the U.N. Security
Council resolutions on Iraq, and the closure of Iraq's weapons
files, starting with the nuclear file, INA said.
</P>
<P>
The closure of the files on Iraq's biological, chemical and
nuclear weapons programs will prepare the ground for lifting the
U.N. sanctions imposed in 1990 after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Aziz and Posuvalyuk discussed Iraq's relationship with the
U.N. Security Council and the outcome of Iraq's recent talks with
the U.N. Special Commission on disarmament in Iraq, or UNSCOM, INA
said.
</P>
<P>
Aziz and UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler on Sunday reached an
agreement on a two-month timetable to end the U.N. disarmament
activities in Iraq if Baghdad fulfills a string of obligations to
prove it has come clean of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Butler said he believed that Iraq was close to be free from the
long-running crippling U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Russia, along with some other permanent members of the Security
Council, has proposed ending the inspection mission in Iraq and
replacing it with long-term monitoring, in order to relieve the
sufferings of the sanction-stricken Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Hailing the Iraqi-Russian relations of cooperation and
friendship, Aziz lauded Moscow's active role in supporting Iraq's
legitimate demands.
</P>
<P>
Aziz once again renewed his call on the international community
to take serious measures to lift the seven-year-old "unjust
sanctions" against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
INA added that the two officials also discussed Russia's supply
of the much-needed basic commodities to Iraq under the fourth
phase of the U.N. oil-for-food program, which allows Iraq to sell
a limited amount of oil for food, medicine and other humanitarian
supplies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
