<HEADLINE> Clinton, Hashimoto talk over Japanese Financial Troubles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
spoke to Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto through
telephone on Tuesday night, a White House official said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"They spoke by phone last night," the official said. But he
declined to provide details of their conversation.
</P>
<P>
They spoke as the Untied States was preparing to send Deputy
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers to Japan and hours before
the Federal Reserve Bank of New York began intervening in
foreign exchange markets for the Treasury Department on behalf
of the yen.
</P>
<P>
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said on Tuesday that he was
concerned about the weak yen and was examining the possibility
of sending Summers to Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
"We've had for a long time concern about the absence of
Japanese growth and we have had great concern about the weakness
of the yen," Rubin said after a lunch with Democrats in the U.S.
Senate.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese currency has tumbled in recent weeks to an
eight-year low as Japan's economy slipped into recession and
Japanese government officials offered no concrete measures for
stimulating activity.
</P>
<P>
"We are deeply concerned about the prolonged weakness of the
Japanese economy," Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has told
a Senate hearing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
