<HEADLINE> Bonn Gives Guarded Welcome to Milosevic's Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
Wednesday praised Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's offer to
alleviate the Kosovo conflict as "an important step in the right
direction."
</P>
<P>
But Kinkel noted that not all the Western demands had been met
and therefore the pressure on Belgrade should be maintained.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel made the remarks after a telephone conservation
Wednesday morning with his Russian counterpart Yevgeni Primakov to
gather information about the talks between Russian President Boris
Yeltsin and Milosevic in Moscow on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Wednesday, Kinkel said that Moscow had
succeeded in pushing through some key demands made by the
six-nation Contact Group, with Milosevic pledging to resume talks
with Kosovo's Albanian leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav president also agreed to provide freedom of
movement in the Serbian province of Kosovo for diplomats and
international humanitarian organizations.
</P>
<P>
However, Kinkel also regretted that Belgrade still refused to
withdraw its troops from Kosovo unconditionally and to accept a
third party in the Kosovo peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations could only be successful when the escalation
of violence and clearing of Kosovo's ethnic Albanians actually
came to a stop, Kinkel said.
</P>
<P>
The German foreign minister said he did not believe it was time
to ease the economic sanctions on Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, western countries would continue to examine military
options in order to maintain pressure, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
