<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt's Effort Last Chance to Save Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian ambassador to Egypt
said Wednesday that Cairo's efforts to coordinate with the parties
concerned may prove to be the "last chance to save the peace march
in the Middle East."
</P>
<P>
Talking to the Middle East News Agency here, Zuhdy Al Qidra
said that moves and contacts made by Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak will in the coming days "define the fate" of the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
"They will reveal to the United States and the entire
international community the truth about the stance of Israel which
rejected the peace approach and challenges the aspirations of the
peoples of the area to realize peace," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said there is a pressing need for the United States, as a
co-sponsor of the peace process, not to submit to Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu who "continues to play with fire and
pursues his expansionist plans which have blocked all roads toward
peace."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) now asks the Arab
nation to agree on a common mechanism capable of confronting
Netanyahu's intransigent policies, the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Qidra warned the situation in the area was taking a "very
dangerous turn," which threatens stability in the area and could
lead to acts of violence, particularly after Israel decided to
form a force of Civil Guards in Jewish settlements in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli decision is a clear call to resort to violence to
seize more Arab land by force, to open the road before Israeli
extremists to attack Palestinians, and to undermine the
restoration of the legitimate rights of Palestinians," he added.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said a careful analysis of the deadlock in the
peace process and latest Israeli statements show that the road of
Palestinian-Israeli negotiations has been fraught with dangers.
</P>
<P>
There is no hope that Israel will accept the U.S. initiative
calling on Israel to withdraw from 13.1 percent more of the West
Bank, which has been accepted by the Palestinian side, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks have been stalled since March
1997 when Israel began work on a new Jewish settlement in Arab
East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Americans have so far failed to convince Israel to accept
its formula of further Israeli redeployment in the West Bank in
exchange for Palestinian crackdown on terrorism, in order to move
the peace wheel forward. 
</P>
</TEXT>
