<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Hopes to Weather Fresh Currency Turmoil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government on
Wednesday expressed the hope that the Philippines will be able to
ride out the financial storm in the midst of the depreciation of
the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Press Secretary Hector Villanueva told reporters
that "if the Japanese economy contracts, the Philippines also will
follow the trend."
</P>
<P>
The yen has been falling against the U.S. dollar recently, with
its exchange rate against the dollar plunging to a record low of
more than 147 to one dollar Monday.
</P>
<P>
Japan, the world's second largest economy, has declared a
recession, worsening unemployment.
</P>
<P>
However, Villanueva said that the Philippines has some strong
points to contend with in the face of the recession in Japan.
</P>
<P>
These are the strong underground economy which serves as a
balancing factor to keep the Philippine economy strong, the income
disparity between the rich and the poor is not too high, and
prices of prime commodities have remained stable.
</P>
<P>
Villanueva admitted that the financial crisis that hit East
Asia, including the Philippines, has caused havoc in the economy.
</P>
<P>
He was hopeful that Japan will shortly recover from the
recession because a long recovery will affect the economy
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
An economist, Villanueva said Asia's economy had overheated in
the mid 1980s due to the unregulated entry of foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
With the East Asian contagion still being felt compounded by
the depreciation of the yen, Villanueva was still optimistic that
"we will ride the storm." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Endeavor Stifles German Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The fiscal austerity program imposed
by Germany to meet the criteria for joining the single European
currency cost the country about 1 percent in economic growth last
year, a leading German economic research institute said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to estimates of the Berlin-based German Institute for
Economic Research (DIW), fiscal restrictions resulting from the
euro endeavor amounted to about 29 billion marks (16.2 billion
U.S. dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to a number of restrictive measures, Germany managed to
cut its budget deficit from 3.6 percent of the gross domestic
product (GDP) in 1996 to 2.7 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Under the European Union's Maastricht Treaty, countries must
cut their 1997 budget deficits to no more than 3 percent of the
GDP in order to qualify for the euro.
</P>
<P>
However, according to the DIW, only about half of Germany's
budget reduction in 1997 actually came from spending cuts.
</P>
<P>
The rest was the result of one-off measures adopted by the
government to increase revenues and of the new calculating methods
used by the German Federal Statistics Office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
