<HEADLINE> Former U.S. Presidents Call for Stronger Ties with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. Presidents George
Bush, Jimmy Carter and Gerald Ford have jointly urged the Congress
to work for a stronger relationship with China.
</P>
<P>
In an unusual move, the three former presidents, together with
seven former secretaries of state, seven former secretaries of
treasury, six former secretaries of defense and five former
national security advisors, signed an open letter to the Congress,
urging the legislators to approve the Most-Favored-Nation (MFN)
trading status for China.
</P>
<P>
"American foreign policy cannot succeed if it fails to engage
China," said the letter, which was published Tuesday in The
Washington Post, The New York Times and other influential
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
"Establishing strong, enduring ties with China has been a
principal objective of American foreign policy since President
(Richard) Nixon's historic visit in 1972, and has been supported
by all subsequent administrations of both parties," it added.
</P>
<P>
"President Clinton's upcoming visit to the People's Republic of
China is a continuation of that policy. It is also an affirmation
of the importance of constructive Sino-American relations at a
critical moment in Asia," the letter said.
</P>
<P>
"It is thus necessary that the visit take place as scheduled,"
the former presidents and secretaries declared. 
</P>
