<HEADLINE> Japan, U.S. Agree to Stabilize foreign Exchange Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto said Wednesday he and U.S. President Bill Clinton had
agreed to cooperate in stabilizing foreign exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders reached the agreement during telephone talks
after the dollar hit an eight-year high earlier this week against
the lackluster Japanese currency.
</P>
<P>
"I agreed with the (U.S.) president that it is preferable for
Japan and the United States to cooperate for a strong yen and the
stabilization of the market," Hashimoto said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dollar hit an eight-year high of the 146.75 yen, the
highest level since August 1990, earlier this week in Tokyo on the
weakness of the Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
In London, the dollar dropped to 138.75 yen after the
U.S. Treasury Department confirmed the U.S. Federal Reserve Board
had intervened in the market by selling the dollar against the
yen, traders said.
</P>
<P>
In Tokyo, the U.S. unit was trading at 141.98-142.01 yen at
5:00 p.m. (local time), after falling to low as 144.10 in early
trading. The Japanese unit traded at 143.35 in New York late
Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
