<HEADLINE> Initiatives in Progress to Get Pak to ASEAN Forum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Diplomatic initiatives are now in
progress to get Pakistan to attend the nuclear non-proliferation
discussions of the upcoming ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF) to be held
here in July, a senior Philippine official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Foreign Affairs Secretary Domingo Siazon, current
chairman of the ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations)
Regional Forum, said the initiatives were taken on the basis of
consensus among ARF members.
</P>
<P>
But Siazon said that the materialization of these initiatives
will largely depend on the agreement by India, Pakistan's arch
enemy.
</P>
<P>
India is a regular member of the ARF, the only existing
security forum in the Asia-Pacific, which groups the nine-member
ASEAN and its 10 other dialogue partners.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has a pending application with the ARF but its recent
nuclear tests in reaction to India's similar nuclear detonations
are expected to discourage its admission into the forum in the
immediate future.
</P>
<P>
Both the nuclear tests by India and Pakistan were strongly
condemned by the international community.
</P>
<P>
Siazon said a prudent approach to the incipient arms race
triggered by the nuclear tests is to get the players to the
conference table.
</P>
<P>
"The ideal is to get Pakistan and India to the same discussion
when the ARF meets in Manila next July, with Pakistan granted only
ad hoc observer status but discussions involving Pakistan will
focus only on nuclear non-proliferation," Siazon explained.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, he explained, needs first to agree to the invitation,
and India to give its consent to the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
The idea of inviting Pakistan to the Manila ARF meeting, Siazon
said, has many proponents and entails diplomats with "closer ties"
with New Delhi and Islamabad "getting in touch with the two
capitals" on an informal basis.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear issue is expected to figure prominently when ARF
foreign ministers meet in Manila.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines, which is now holding the rotating ASEAN
chairmanship, will host its ministerial meeting and the ARF
conference in late July.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN's dialogue partners in the ARF include Australia, Canada,
China, Japan, India, Russia, New Zealand, the United States and
the European Union. Cambodia and Papua New Guinea are observers in
the ARF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
