<HEADLINE> Blatter Says Riots not to Affect England's Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- FIFA President Sepp Blatter said here on
Wednesday the violences involving England fans in Marseille would not
affect England's bid for the World Cup finals in 2006.
</P>
<P>
"There is not relation between each other," said Blatter. "What
happened in France will have no influence on the decision to be made
by the executive committee."
</P>
<P>
The Swiss added, "It is not only hooligans from England, but also
Germany, who were sent to jail in the correct measures taken by the
French authorities. The incident should have no impact on the 2006
World Cup bid."
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of England supporters clashed with Tunisian fans in the 48
hours before the game that pitted the two team against each other in
gropu G.
</P>
<P>
Violence also broke out on a beach between them during the game,
which was won by England 2-0.
</P>
<P>
Blatter said FIFA and the French organizing committe would work
closely with the French police to prevent any recurrence of violence.
</P>
<P>
He added that he was happy to see there had been no clashes among
fans in the venues.
</P>
<P>
The president said the selection of a Swiss referee for the group F
game between Iran and United States on Sunday was a careful decision.
</P>
<P>
"There was not a coincidence," said Blatter. "We think we have to
chose somebody from a country which has good relationship with both
countries." 
</P>
</TEXT>
