<HEADLINE> 2 Israeli Soldiers Wounded in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Two Israeli soldiers were wounded
in south Lebanon by a roadside bomb overnight, the Orient Radio
reported here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The bomb was detonated by remote control about midnight Tuesday
when an Israeli patrol was driving along a road near the village
of Hadatha in the western sector of the Israeli-occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has claimed in a
statement responsibility for the attack, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Six Israeli soliders have been killed and 64 others injured in
south Lebanon so far this year.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip in
south Lebanon in 1985 as security zone, with the claimed aim of
protecting its northern areas from Lebanese guerrilla cross-border
attacks.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah has been spearheading a guerrilla war in south
Lebanon against some 1,500 Israeli occupation troops and their
allied 2,500-strong South Lebanon Army militia. 
</P>
