<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The weakening Japanese yen has
started to hit the Hungarian economy, sending stock prices down
and affecting the forint, the national currency, the Nepszabadsag
newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The yen would further affect the national economy, which was
already straining under the knock-on affects of the recent
parliamentary elections and the lackluster Russian economy,
according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Hungary has a trade deficit against Japan with Japanese-funded
automobile and electronic firms importing large amounts of
equipment and parts from Japan.
</P>
<P>
The yen's weakness would further increase the deficit, helping
Japanese exports, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the exchange rate averaged one forint to seven yen,
but it is expected to rise to one to 10 this year because of the
yen's devaluation. 
</P>
