<HEADLINE> Blatter Says Referee Work Needs Improvement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Joseph Sepp Blatter, president of
international soccer governing body FIFA, said here on Wednesday the
refereeing in the World Cup finals still needed improvement.
</P>
<P>
"I said refereeing is generally good but should improve. It should
not be described 'excellent' because of the lack of rigor against
tackling from behind.," the president said.
</P>
<P>
"I saw a tackling from behind in a match yesterday but the referee
did not show the red card," said Blatter.
</P>
<P>
After 18 group games in the tournament, only South Korea's Ha Seok
Ju was sent off for tackling from behind.
</P>
<P>
Blatter added that the goalkeepers who had not followed the new
rules in the first days of the competition were not dealt with by the
referees either.
</P>
<P>
According the latest rules, the goalkeeper could not handle the
ball more than six seconds or four steps before releasing it.
</P>
<P>
The president, who was elected on June 8 in the FIFA Congress here,
backed the decision of referee Lucian Bouchardeau from Niger to award
a penalty kick to Italy in their 2-2 draw with Chile.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know why there are rumors that Mr. Bouchardeau has been
sent home. Bouchardeau did his job as a referee properly. A player
touched the ball and Bouchardeau made his judgement whether it was
unintentional. And it was right." Blatter said.
</P>
<P>
Roberto Baggio converted the spot kick, giving Italy the equalizer
in their first group match. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
