<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Inner Cabinet Fails to Decide on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Amid reports that some progress
has been made over further Israeli pullback from the West Bank,
Israeli inner cabinet met Wednesday to discuss the issue, but no
result was yielded.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that the members of the inner cabinet,
namely, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai, National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon
and Minister of Industry and Trade Natan Sharansky, will meet
again in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held after Netanyahu confirmed Tuesday night
that there has been progress in the Israeli-U.S. contacts over the
redeployment. Speaking on Israeli television, the prime minister
said a decision on the scope of the second pullback has not been
made, but he believes that an agreement could be reached soon.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Tuesday, Israel Radio quoted diplomatic sources as
saying that Israel and the U.S. have made headway in their
negotiations over the further redeployment, which Israel says the
negotiations are centering on.
</P>
<P>
Israel has been seeking a "total package" concerning the
further redeployments from the West Bank. In another word, it is
trying to include the third redeployment into the second pullback
agreement. Some believe that by doing so, Israel hopes to minimize
the scope of the third redeployment.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, in a seldom
expression of cautious optimism, also said Tuesday that she
believes Israel and the Palestinians could reach an agreement on
the redeployment. Speaking at a Senate hearing, she said that the
U.S. will continue its efforts "so long as we believe that Israel
and Palestinians are serious about doing so."
</P>
<P>
But there are sharp difference in Israel's inner cabinet over
how to continue the negotiations with the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Mordechai has stressed on many occasions that the time has come
for a redeployment decision. He also said that "as much as
possible" should be finalized concerning the third withdrawal in
order to move ahead to the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
But Sharon, the leading hawk in the cabinet, insisted that
Israel, now more than ever, should stand firm to safeguard its
vital security interests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
