<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cease-Fire Pact Reached by Somali Factions in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A reconciliation meeting of the
Islamic fundamentalist Al-Itihad al-Islam, the Somali National
Front (SNF) and the Marehan subclan has been concluded in
El-Addeh village in the Somali border region of Gedo.
</P>
<P>
Ali Nur, deputy chairman of the SNF factions, who attended the
meeting, said delegates had agreed upon an immediate cease-fire,
the cessation of all hostilities, and the re-encampment of the
opposing militiamen back to their former barracks, effective from
June 15 onward.
</P>
<P>
The leaders who contacted Xinhua in Mogadishu via VHF radio
characterized the reconciliation meeting as "historic and
fruitful in fostering peace in Gedo region" bordering on
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
According to Sheikh Mohamud Moallim Nur, the deputy chairman
of Al-Itihad Al-Islam, the meeting concluded two days ago was
prompted by the call of Marehan traditional leader Ugas Omar Ugas
Hirsi, following the increased restlessness and armed skirmishes
in the region between the feuding groups.
</P>
<P>
The elders said all the roads abandoned due to the hostilities
will be reopened to traffic and commercial activities between the
districts of the region and the country at large.
</P>
<P>
The conference also resolved that another follow-up meeting
will be convened in the same village on July 15.
</P>
<P>
The border region of Gedo had been the center of conflicts
between the SNF faction of General Omar Haggi Massale and those
of the deposed Al-Itihad militiamen after Ethiopian forces
supported by the Marehan SNF militiamen to control of the
border towns of Dolow, Bulo Hawo and Luq in late 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian forces pulled out of the region last year after
Somali faction leaders including General Omar Haggi Massale
signed an agreement in Cairo late last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the agreement was not recognized by Ethiopia.
</P>
</TEXT>
