<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- The Ministry of Agriculture of the Palestinian National
Authority has announced that Saudi Arabia has imported from
Palestine 13,000 tonnes agricultural products during the current
agricultural season.
</P>
<P>
Khalid Zarid, the ministry's marketing director, said that
since Saudi Arabia exempted Palestinian agricultural products from
customs duties, the country's imports from Palestine have
increased more than 10 folds from last year's imports.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- The Damascus Chamber of Commerce has announced that
the first private company in Syria has been set up for the
marketing of vegetables, fruits and agricultural products with a
capital of 8 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The company is aimed at seeking outlets for world markets,
especially the European markets, the Syrian News Agency reported
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It assumes special importance after Syria's decision to sign
the Euro-Mediterranean partnership agreement.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Belarus have signed nine agreements on
activating cooperation, avoidance of double taxation and promotion
of trade, the Egyptian Alam Al Yom daily reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The agreements signed on Tuesday cover cooperation in the
fields of transport, education, information, veterinary medicine,
utilization of natural resources and transfer of technology.
</P>
<P>
The two countries agreed to set up a joint supreme committee to
follow up bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Chairman of the Egyptian General Authority for
Investments Ibrahim Fawzi has said that infrastructure works and
public utilities in Suez gulf and the eastern sub-Suez canal zone
will enjoy tax exemption, in implementation of the law of
incentives and investment guarantees, the Alam Al Yom daily
reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But Fawzi said that contracting works do not enjoy the favors
given by the law, under which exemptions cover those activities
which face investment risks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
