<HEADLINE> Most Israelis Surveyed Accept 13 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 17 (Xinhua) -- In a recent opinion poll, most
Israelis surveyed expressed readiness to accept that Israel
withdraws troops from another 13 percent of the West Bank, the
Yediot Aharonot daily reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the opinion poll conducted by Hadaf for the daily,
59 percent of the surveyed said they were in favor of the
withdrawal scope.
</P>
<P>
The United States has reportedly put forward the proposal in a
bid to break the deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
The Palestinians have accepted the proposal, but Israel has not.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 people in all walks of life across the country
were surveyed in the opinion poll.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that 74 percent of the surveyed think that it
is necessary to continue the peace talks and implement the signed
peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
But more than half of the surveyed do not think that Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu wants to carry out the
agreements.
</P>
<P>
The peace process between Israel and the Palestinians has been
deadlocked since March 1997 when Israel began construction of a
Jewish settlement in traditionally Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
It is now mainly stalled over Israel's further troop pullback
from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The error rate of the survey is 4.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Announces Ambitious Housing Reform Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government today
announced an ambitious market-oriented housing reform plan aimed
at providing better dwellings for its urban residents.
</P>
<P>
The plan, declared at a national housing reform conference
which closed here today, will end the long-practiced welfare
housing distribution system for government officials and
enmployees of state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Under the new plan, workers will be encouraged to buy houses
with their salary or bank loans as the newly completed houses will
be sold, instead of rented, to the dwellers in pricinple.
</P>
<P>
The reform also calls for the introduction of a multi-layered
housing supply system to meet the needs of people of different
incomes.
</P>
<P>
Under such a system, high-grade apartments and houses will be
sold at market prices; medium-income families will enjoy housing
sold at government-directed prices; and low-income families will
receive government-set low-rent dwellings.
</P>
<P>
The conference stressed the importance of expanding
investment in economical apartments and dwellings and called for
curbs on the excessively high land and housing prices and profits
in major cities.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also called for expanded and better financial
support and services for urban home buyers, allowing all
commercial banks to provide mortgage loans with no amount limits
to potential buyers.
</P>
<P>
In his speech delivered at the meeting, Vice Premier Wen Jiabao
emphasized the importance of introducing the housing reform in an
active and steady manner.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the deepening of the reform will help turn
housing construction into a new growth point of the national
economy.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts observed that, despite progress in housing
reform in recent years, the market mechanism still cannot play its
proper role in the construction, distribution and marketing of
housing. If housing reform is not deepened, the reform in other
sectors will be affected, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
They stressed the importance of housing reform in achieving the
goal for this year's economic growth and in creating new jobs.
</P>
<P>
They also pointed out that deepening the reform of the housing
system is also a need for the constant rise in the people's living
standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: China Expecting Housing Sector Growth Li Jianmin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- China is working on a new housing
reform for commercializing housing that is expected to promote
growth in the housing sector.
</P>
<P>
Under a new plan, new affordable housing will be sold to
workers and staff only. The workers and staff have to purchase
apartments by themselves by using the housing subsidies, public
housing fund and bank loans, according to a Ministry of
Construction official.
</P>
<P>
This will bring China's welfare-based housing allocation
system, which has been operating for nearly 50 years, to a
complete halt, and demand for affordable housing is expected to
increase sharply. China is planning to spend 41.9 billion yuan
this year building nearly 49 million sq.m. of housing, the
ministry says.
</P>
<P>
To increase the average per capita urban living space to 9
sq.m. by the end of the century, the country has to build 175
million sq.m. annually and renovate or rebuild 200 million
sq.m. of old housing annually.
</P>
<P>
The housing reform is meant to bring rational and stable
development to the real estate sector, mainly in affordable
housing projects to improve the standard of living and to make the
housing sector a pillar of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The effort to reform the housing market by selling housing to
Chinese rather than using housing as a benefit at the work unit
will play a decisive role in developing the market.
</P>
<P>
To stimulate this, commercial banks have begun to provide
mortgages, and a nationwide fund system is providing assistance
for private housing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
