<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Invites Afghan Parties to Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar
Ayub Khan said here Wednesday that Pakistan has invited
representatives from Afghanistan's Taliban militia and their rival
Northern Alliance to work out formulas to press forward their
deadlocked peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"We have invited one representative from each side to meet here
to decide on some sort of formula for their possible talks in the
future," Gohar told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Afghanistan early this month, Pakistani
State Minister for Foreign Affairs Siddique Khan Kanju conveyed
this proposal to the leadership of both the Taliban and the
Northern Alliance, Gohar said.
</P>
<P>
"We are still waiting for the confirmation from both sides," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said Pakistan and Iran, as the two immediate
neighbors of Afghanistan, are trying to establish "a mechanism" in
which the two countries can work together to bring about peace in
war-torn Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan peace process has been in jeopardy following the
break-up of the Joint Steering Committee meeting which was
attended by five delegates from the Taliban and nine from the
alliance early May in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
The Steering Committee meeting, sponsored by the United Nations
and the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC), was aimed at
establishing the Taliban-proposed Ulema (religious scholars)
Commission, which will decide the future political set-up in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban militia have already given up the idea of holding a
 dialogue with the Northern Alliance under the proposed Ulema
Commission as the alliance had disrespected this commission, the
Taliban's envoy Abdul Hakim Mujahid told Xinhua here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He called for new initiatives from the U.N., OIC and other
neighboring countries for the resumption of the Afghan peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
"Since the Afghan Steering Committee has slowed down and made
little progress, we are trying to make new proposals so that they
(the Afghan talks) can start," Gohar said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the peace mediation in Afghanistan was no easy
job as the Taliban, who control two-thirds of Afghanistan, and the
alliance, who holds the remaining one-third, "are still looking
for a military solution."
</P>
<P>
"The Taliban feel that over a long period of time they might be
able to take control of all of Afghanistan while the alliance
thinks that if they have limited military success, their
bargaining position would be better," he said.
</P>
<P>
He regretted that the rigid stances held by the two groups
would lead to more bloodshed and suffering in a country where the
infrastructure has been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
"We have been trying to bring them here on numerous occasions,
so that a broad-based government could be formed in Afghanistan.
We are trying all options whichever we succeed," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's new peace initiative in Afghanistan came just days
after a two-day visit to Pakistan by Iranian Foreign Minister
Kamal Kharazi early June.
</P>
<P>
Gohar said during Kharazi's visit both countries agreed to
enhance their joint efforts in seeking peace in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He said: "Now we are trying to get a mechanism in which both of
us can work together for this purpose."
</P>
<P>
However, he emphasized that the final solution should come from
the Afghans themselves.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister described the U.N. role in the Afghan
peace process as "very positive." "But a little more
understanding and encouragement from the U.N. would be
reciprocated by the Taliban," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
