<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African IT Show Opens in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The seventh African Information
Technology (IT) Exhibition and Conference (AITEC) opened in
downtown Nairobi with at least 5,000 visitors expected.
</P>
<P>
"The dramatic growth this year in the size of the exhibition
reflects the increasing importance and penetration of information
technology in Kenya's economy," said Kenyan Minister for Research
and Technology Andrew Kiptoon in his opening speech.
</P>
<P>
"The information technology is synonymous to development,"
Kiptoon stressed, calling for the promotion of IT in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
About 65 companies including IBM, Microsoft, Compaq and other
worldwide computer giants attended the show set to end on June
22, said the chief organizer, Sean Moroney.
</P>
<P>
The theme of this year's show and conference is "Developing an
IT Strategy for the New Millennium."
</P>
<P>
"Now IT has become the mainstream and Kenya has become part
and parcel of that growth," Moroney claimed.
</P>
<P>
"When we first launched AITEC seven years ago, we were seen as
ahead of our time," he recalled.
</P>
<P>
Kenya, hosting about 8,000 Internet users, remains east
Africa's largest information IT market valued at some 63.5
million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Moroney said the exhibitors and experts will explore the
global trends in computing and internet management as well as
look at the risks, costs and effectiveness of re-engineering old
systems versus investing in new systems.
</P>
<P>
"Since we began the AITEC shows in this region, they have
become milestones in computing development. They don't just
showcase new products but also bring information on global trends
and relate them to the local IT environment," he said.
</P>
<P>
This year's conference will also focus on preparedness for
what has come to be known as the "millennium bug" -- a shutdown
of computer and electronic systems which are not programmed for
the year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
The workshop is expected to attract IT managers, upper-level
operations managers, IT professionals, software consultants and
service organizations, IT vendors and so on. Some 7,000 visitors
attended last year's event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
