<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Adhere to Fiscal Prudence: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Financial Secretary Donald Tsang
 said here Wednesday that Hong Kong would adhere to fiscal
prudence despite the current economic woes.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the media after discussing the 1999-2000 Budget
with members-elect of the first Legislative Council, Tsang
emphasized: "The Budget is an instrument for economic growth and
an instrument to address social problems."
</P>
<P>
The financial secretary said that he had to balance the pleas
for tax reduction and greater expenditure, which would relieve the
 pains of present economic adjustment, with the expectation of
international investors, who would want to see Hong Kong
continuing its prudent financial management principle.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law, the constitutional document of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR), stipulates that the SAR will
follow the principle of keeping expenditure within the limits of
revenues in drawing up its budget, and strive to achieve a fiscal
balance, avoid deficits and keep the budget commensurate with the
growth rate of its gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
The trend growth rate for the past few years was five percent,
said Tsang, who predicted that it would be unlikely that Hong Kong
 would sustain five-percent growth in real terms in the coming few
 years.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that the economic slowdown would grossly limit the
new resources available for new expenditure in the coming
financial year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
