<HEADLINE> Chinese Publishers Want To Help Save Tibetan Culture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- China's publishers plan to spend
15 million yuan (1.8 million US dollars) to print books on Tibetan
culture, some of which have long been out of print.
</P>
<P>
Yang Muzhi, deputy director of China's Press and Publications
Administration, said today that 18 publishers will cooperate with
the Tibet Publishing House in 26 categories of books on the Dalai
Lama, Tibetan history, Buddhism, the arts, astrology, Tibetan
language, traditional medicine, and other areas. One of them will
be a large dictionary on Tibetan history and culture containing 14
million characters and 1,600 photos, Yang says.
</P>
<P>
Gong Xinhan, the deputy head of the Chinese Communist Party
Central Committee's Publicity Department, calls it a major step in
protecting Tibetan culture.
</P>
<P>
The publications show that the statements that "Tibetan
people's human rights have been violated and Tibetan culture has
been destroyed" are totally groundless, Gong says.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, some 17 million yuan has been donated by various
publishers to support Tibet's publishing industry, and Yang
explains, "Tibetan culture is a part of Chinese culture, and the
Party and the government have been placing great importance on
preserving it."
</P>
<P>
China has set up institutes to collect, record, and study
Tibetan culture and a lot of works have been published, he says,
but the Tibetan publishing industry is faced with a lack of money,
equipment, and skilled workers, so the cooperation with the
rest part of the country will be very helpful. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
