<HEADLINE> Japanese Parliament Approves Extra Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Japan's House of Councillors (upper
house of parliament) on Wednesday endorsed a pump-priming
supplementary budget for the 1998 fiscal year, paving the way for
the latest government package of economic stimulus measures.
</P>
<P>
The 4.6 trillion yen (32.1 billion U.S. dollars) extra budget,
which was approved at a plenary session of the upper house,
cleared the powerful House of Representatives, or lower house, on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The supplementary budget is part of the 16.65 trillion yen
(116.4 billion dollars) stimulus package, which the government
expects will put the floundering domestic economy back on a
recovery track later this year.
</P>
<P>
The budget enables additional government spending and special
tax cuts totalling 6.1 trillion yen (about 42.7 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
With the passage of the extra budget, government expenditure
will rise to 82.31 trillion yen (575.6 billion dollars) this
financial year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
