<HEADLINE> Police Forces of Inland Areas, Macao Cooperate to Combat Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Police from the Interpol China
National Bureau and its Macao Branch held a meeting here today to
discuss their cooperation in maintaining the social stability of
Macao.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed that closer cooperation between police forces
in the inland areas and Macao will be necessary to maintain
Macao's social security and its smooth transition in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Expressing concerns about serious crimes in Macao recently, the
public security department in the inland areas reiterated that the
Portuguese government will be responsible for administering Macao
until Dec. 20, 1999, according to the Sino-Portuguese Joint
Declaration.
</P>
<P>
The Macao police are expected to take positive measures to
maintain the social security of the region, while the public
security department of the inland areas will help crack down on
crimes involving the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also agreed to increase cooperation on cross-border
crimes, information exchange and the capture of crime suspects.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Entao, assistant minister of Public Security and chief
representative of the China National Bureau of Interpol, and Macao
counterpart Antonio Francisco Marques Baptista attended the
meeting, which is scheduled to end Friday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
