<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Chinese Military Officers Visit Harvard (1) (by Peng Shujie and Liu Yunfei) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A delegation of 23 senior Chinese
military officers from the People's Liberation Army (PLA) attended
a two week training course at Harvard University in March.
</P>
<P>
The delegation was the second group of PLA officers to complete
studies at Harvard, a highly prestigious university with a history
of 362 years.
</P>
<P>
Former U.S. Assistant Secretary of Defense Joseph Nye,
president of Harvard's Kennedy School of Government, initiated the
Annual Harvard Senior Military Officers program in 1997 with the
support of defense ministries in both countries.
</P>
<P>
The two-week course featured some 40-odd seminars on topics
ranging from Sino-U.S. relations and security in the Asia-Pacific
Region to nuclear nonproliferation and information warfare.
</P>
<P>
The PLA officers, most of whom were visiting the United States
for the first time, spent two weekends visiting U.S. warships, the
headquarters of the United Nations, the Pentagon and Capitol Hill,
as well as military bases and farms. The delegation also enjoyed
NBA basketball and stage performances.
</P>
<P>
"USS Constitution"
</P>
<P>
The first day of sightseeing included a visit to the USS
Constitution, an over 200 year old warship still in symbolic
service in Boston Harbor. The vessel, which is armed with 50-odd
cannons, has achieved a remarkable record since the War of
Independence in 1775.
</P>
<P>
"My deepest impression was that backwardness leaves one
vulnerable," according to Senior Colonel Wang Guanzhong, a Chinese
specialist in national defense strategic military studies.
</P>
<P>
"Our American hosts obviously used the ship to exemplify the
spirit their ancestors exhibited over two centuries ago during
efforts to catch-up with Britain and other European powers," said
Wang.
</P>
<P>
"We have entered the era of information warfare at a time when
the Chinese army has not yet completed preparations for overall
mechanization. We must maintain a sense of urgency and extend
great efforts to catch-up with advanced countries in order to
prevent being left behind," said Wang, who overcame his limited
English by relying on interpreters during his studies at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
"We formerly paid close attention to new types of weapons
developed by foreign armies and neglected the role of information
technology in modern warfare.
</P>
<P>
"Discussions with our American counterparts and visits to
U.S. military bases helped me realize that the use of high
technology to upgrade conventional weapons helps to multiply
combat capabilities. Applications of information technology can
significantly enhance the control and guidance of forces during
wartime, while at the same time uniting surveillance, guidance
systems and combat troops," according to Wang.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Chinese Military Officers Visit Harvard (2) (by Peng Shujie and Liu Yunfei) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Woman Naval Captain's Argument
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan issue, a core issue in Sino-U.S. relations, was
obviously a focal point during discussions between Chinese
officers and their American counterparts. The most heated
discussions took place between Lei Xiaoping, the only female
captain in the Chinese Navy, and a U.S. researcher on the staff of
the congressional Foreign Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
The researcher told participants in one seminar that China's
1996 missile exercises created a crisis in the Taiwan Straits
which was resulted from China's misunderstanding of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
He commented that Deng Xiaoping once said that the Taiwan issue
could either be dealt in a step by step manner or could otherwise
be passed and settled by the next generation.
</P>
<P>
The researcher completed his presentation and Lei immediately
commented that the missile exercise was a normal military
manoeuvre. She noted that the exercises were preceded by a public
announcement and were carried out in strict accordance with
international conventions.
</P>
<P>
"Lee Teng-Hui's visit to the United States in 1995 has been
widely acknowledged as encouraging forces calling for
Taiwan's 'independence' and creating the crisis in the straits,"
said Lei in fluent English. "In addition, your reference to Deng
Xiaoping's remarks on Taiwan were totally inaccurate. His comments
were in fact referring to the Diaoyu Islands."
</P>
<P>
Lei informed the researcher that both China and the United
States will suffer losses if bilateral relations deteriorate
because of the Taiwan issue, and noted that the latter might even
sustain heavier losses.
</P>
<P>
"The only wise approach for the U.S. government is to strictly
abide by the three Sino-U.S. joint communiques and cease selling
military hardware to Taiwan rather than dispatching aircraft
carriers," said Lei.
</P>
<P>
Lei's precise and clear comments left a deep impression on
Americans attending the seminar. Major Roy Kamphausen, assistant
military attache-designate to the U.S. Embassy in China, commented
in Chinese: "Captain Lei, you are really sharp."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
