<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Chinese Military Officers Visit Harvard (3) (by Peng Shujie and Liu Yunfei) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
United Nations Visit
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation visited the United Nations headquarters
on their last weekend in the United States. The group paused
before entering the building to view two sculptures, one of which
was the twisted barrel of a rifle and the other is a cracked globe.
</P>
<P>
"The pieces represent the massive damages the earth and human
beings have suffered at the hands of war," said Colonel Jiang Lei,
one of the first Ph.D. graduates from the Chinese Academy of
Military Sciences. "The world is far from peaceful despite the
fact that peace and development are the two major themes in
today's world. Arms race and regional conflicts continue to
surface from time to time," said Jiang
</P>
<P>
"This poses a question for world leaders and soldiers
concerning whether the security of one country can be built on the
insecurity of another nation," said Jiang. "The world will enjoy
real peace only after this particular concept of defense is
abandoned."
</P>
<P>
"China, the world's most populous and largest developing
country, and the United States, the most developed country, have
the responsibility to raise relations to a new plateau regardless
of differing ideologies and social systems," according to Jiang.
</P>
<P>
Strength Forms the Foundation for Equal Contacts
</P>
<P>
"Strength speaks the loudest and it is the foundation for equal
contacts; this is my deepest impression of the two-week stay
there," said Colonel Li Jiang, an expert on China's national
defense policy and strategy.
</P>
<P>
"If China had not made the crusade of reforms and opening to
the outside world 20 years ago, and the country was not
politically stable and economically prosperous nowadays, and it
has not played a bigger role in world affairs, it is hardly
imaginable for us to sit in the classrooms of Harvard."
</P>
<P>
"The meticulous arrangement of our American host is also a good
demonstration of it," Li said, who has visited the former Soviet
Union and Romania.
</P>
<P>
"Thus, we must always keep in our mind that national
development should be the most important task at any time for any
one of us," Li emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Although the U.S. and Chinese sides agreed that this new type
of exchange is beneficial for both of them to learn from each
other, the Chinese officers admitted that two weeks is far from
being adequate to understand a country, especially a country like
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Information from the Ministry of National Defense says that
defense ministries of both countries have the willingness to
continue this program, and they are now working to perfect it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0143 </DOCNO>
