<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks jumped 6.3
percent Wednesday as interbank rates eased due to a stronger
Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng Index leapt 477.9 points to register the
day's closing trading figure at 8,004.35, its second straight gain
following a 0.86-percent rise Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two-day rise recovered some of the loss it suffered from
the more-than-three-year low of 7,462.5 points on Monday. The
plunge was caused by rising local interbank rates and increasing
pressure from the weakening Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
The market's turnover on Wednesday amounted to 6.143 billion HK
dollars (788 million U.S. dollars), 1.431 billion HK dollars (183
million U.S. dollars) more than that of Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index registered a gain of 261.38 points, or 3.47
percent, to open at 7,787.83 Wednesday morning. It rose 273.9
points, or 3.63 percent, to close at 7,800.1 at midday.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong shares rose 63.95 points to close at 7,526.45 points
on Tuesday. 
</P>
