<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Image Has Improved Since HK's Return: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- China's image has been improved
by the way it has managed Hong Kong in the last year, according to
the majority of respondents to the latest Asian Executives Poll,
carried out jointly by the Far Eastern Economic Review and CNBC
Asia.
</P>
<P>
A majority of Asian executives (51 percent) say China is viewed
in a better light since Hong Kong returned to China on July 1,
1997. In Hong Kong, 76 percent of those polled say China's image
has improved.
</P>
<P>
Overall, 63 percent across the region say closer Sino-American
ties would be good for Asia-wide security. When asked the same
question last year, 58 percent thought improved ties would boost
security.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Executives Poll is a weekly fax poll conducted by the
Far Eastern Economic Review and CNBC Asia. Respondents are
chairman, managing directors and other top corporate executives in
10 Asian countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Singapore-based CNBC Asia is a service of Dow Jones and
Company, publisher of The Wall Street Journal, and National
Broadcasting Corporation (NBC) is one of the leading television
networks in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Wholly owned by Dow Jones and Company, The Far Eastern Economic
Review is Asia's first regional publication. 
</P>
</TEXT>
