<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani-Indian PM Meeting in Colombo Hopeful: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar
Ayub Khan said here Wednesday that Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and
his Indian counterpart will "hopefully" hold a formal meeting at
the forthcoming SAARC summit next month.
</P>
<P>
"We would have a formal meeting with the Indian prime minister
in Colombo next month and hopefully the two prime ministers will
meet there," Gohar said in an interview with Xinhua Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 10th summit meeting of the seven-nation South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) is to take place in
Colombo, capital of Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
"We have told the Indian government about this on numerous
occasions and we will formally communicate with them shortly that
the two prime ministers would meet in Sri Lanka," Gohar said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister emphasized the need for Pakistan and India
to resume their bilateral talks as the situation in South Asia
"has become so volatile after the two countries have acquired
nuclear weapons" following their nuclear tests last month.
</P>
<P>
He called for more active and positive international engagement
in the dialogue process between Pakistan and India to ensure its
success.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the expected meeting between the two
prime ministers will help push forward the foreign secretary-level
talks which broke down last September in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, "We have to see the approach of the Indian
leadership as to how they reciprocate the Pakistani proposal for a
meaningful dialogue on Kashmir."
</P>
<P>
"With seriousness we address the issue, hopefully we can kick
off from there," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan proposed last Friday that the foreign
secretary-level talks be resumed on the basis of the agreement
reached between the two sides on June 23 last year in Islamabad,
under which eight issues including peace and security, Jammu and
Kashmir would be discussed in their future talks.
</P>
<P>
He regretted that the Indian government failed to respond
positively to the Pakistani proposal, instead it unilaterally
announced that the bilateral talks would be held on June 22 on the
basis of the draft proposals it made in January.
</P>
<P>
Gohar termed the proposals made by India in January when Sharif
and his then Indian counterpart, I.K. Gujral, met in Dhaka,
capital of Bangladesh, as "unpractical and unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
India suggested that each of the eight issues on the agreed
agenda of talks be headed by a secretary of a ministry, meaning
that eight groups would be sitting simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a practical solution. It indicates that there is a
lack of seriousness on the Indian side to implement such a serious
issue," Gohar said.
</P>
<P>
"Basically it is to create more issues out of the talks, to
prolong the sessions and not come to a solution," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he reiterated that the bilateral talks between
Pakistan and India will not bear fruits unless the international
community seriously involves itself in the political process.
</P>
<P>
Since March 28 last year to January 15 this year, Pakistan and
India have held three rounds of foreign secretary-level talks, one
foreign minister-level meeting and four prime minister-level
meetings, he said, adding that "unfortunately, none of these talks
produced any positive results."
</P>
<P>
"If we continue talks still on a bilateral basis, the talks
will be again fruitless. We are just going through an exercise
with a knowledge that there will be hardly any progress," he said.
</P>
<P>
"So it is high time for a third party to channelize efforts, to
give direction and ensure certain amount of constructive and
positive outcome through these talks," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Putonghua Gaining Popularity in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Luk Hon Tak just completed a
12-session middle-level Putonghua course to polish his standard
spoken Chinese.
</P>
<P>
As most Hong Kong people were, the middle-aged Luk was educated
in English, the official working language, and Cantonese, the
dialect spoken by 98 percent of Hong Kong's 6.5 million
population.
</P>
<P>
In his memory, Putonghua was only heard in Mandarin songs 20
years ago. Today, Luk, a corporate affairs manager at Hongkong
Telecom, speaks Putonghua almost every day in his frequent contact
with mainland media and telecommunications circles.
</P>
<P>
"It (speaking Putonghua) is a trend that every one can see,"
said Luk. "If you can speak Putonghua, you master a necessary tool
of communication."
</P>
<P>
The number of people learning Putonghua has surged dramatically
over the past two decades, according to Sin Kam Wai, principal of
Hong Kong Putonghua Society, a non-government and non-profit
organization devoted to the promotion of Putonghua since 1976.
</P>
<P>
In its early days, the Society enrolled at most several hundred
students a year. The number surpassed 10,000 in the mid-1980s, and
eventually jumped to about 20,000 per year around the handover on
July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The momentum continued into the first year after Hong Kong
became a Special Administrative Region (SAR) of China, enjoying a
high degree of autonomy under the "one country, two systems"
formula. Close economic interaction and rising exchanges between
Hong Kong and the mainland have driven more and more Hong Kong
residents to pick up Putonghua, the language spoken by their 1.2
billion compatriots on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is the biggest overseas investor in China, and China,
the second largest trading partner of Hong Kong. Today one out of
four tourists arriving in Hong Kong come from the mainland.
</P>
<P>
"Putonghua can provide you an opportunity to tap the mainland
market, the biggest and nearest for Hong Kong, and put you a few
notches above others in the competitive job market," Sin added.
That is why an increasing number of government institutions and
private companies organize Putonghua classes for staff members,
which always get an active response.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Putonghua has entered the daily life of the common
people. Telephone users can dial to a new hotline that provides
Putonghua service, passengers can hear Putonghua announcements on
the trains running along the Kowloon-Canton railway, and radio
audience can tune in a Putonghua channel.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to promote the use of the mother tongue, the SAR
government has asked the 1,500 middle and primary schools in Hong
Kong to open Putonghua courses in September this year. Students
are encouraged to master English and Chinese, both working
languages in the SAR, and speak English, Cantonese and Putonghua.
</P>
<P>
A mother who invites a Putonghua teacher for her five-year-old
child said she did so "because I clearly know that Putonghua is
tomorrow's language in Hong Kong." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese State Councillor Meets with British Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- China understands and respects the
change in Britain's policy for assistance to China, Chinese State
Councillor Wu Yi said today.
</P>
<P>
During her meeting with Clare Short, Britain's Secretary of
State for International Development, Wu said that China began its
financial cooperation with Britain in 1986, and until now, Britain
has offered 800 million pounds in mixed loans, which have been put
into 43 projects.
</P>
<P>
She expressed her hope that the new British government would
continue to implement the agreements between China and the former
British administration.
</P>
<P>
Short promised that the government of Prime Minister Tony Blair
would carry out the concluded accords as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
The new British government changed its policy of cooperation
with China by mainly providing it with donations rather than mixed
loans.
</P>
<P>
Short said that this policy change is aimed at more effective
use of Britain's assistance to China, and that the amount of the
assistance could increase in the future.
</P>
<P>
She added that the British side is interested in cooperating
with China in such areas as culture and education, health care,
reform of state-owned enterprises and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Wu spoke highly of the positive approach of the British in the
conduct of its financial cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
Wu expressed her hope that the two sides would implement
cooperative projects in these fields as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Short said that although the Blair government took office less
than one year ago, many cabinet members have visited China, which
indicates that the British government values its ties with
China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
