<HEADLINE> Tung Chee Hwa Praises Success in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive of China's Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region Tung Chee Hwa Wednesday praised
the success achieved in Hong Kong after it returned to the embrace
of China last July.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a dinner in New Zealand's largest city of Auckland
hosted by the New Zealand Asia 2000 Foundation, Tung said, "Eleven
months have gone by since July 1. The central leadership has shown
great determination to implement the principle of 'one country,
two systems', 'Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong' with a 'high
degree of autonomy'."
</P>
<P>
"We in Hong Kong are also determined to ensure the full
implementation of the Basic Law. Indeed, the success is manifested
every day in Hong Kong and in every possible way. I invite you to
come and see for yourselves," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
On the current financial crisis in Asia, he described it as
being "painful to us all."
</P>
<P>
"But the fundamentals in Asia haven't changed. We still have a
young and flexible workforce, a very high savings rate, openness
to trade and ideas and an indomitable spirit to improve ourselves.
Some glaring uncertainties still need to be resolved, but I would
expect the Asian financial crisis to bottom out in a number of
years and we shall then witness a slow but sure road toward
recovery."
</P>
<P>
On the question of whether China will devalue its currency, the
renminbi (RMB), Tung said that in his view, the answer is no.
</P>
<P>
"China's leaders have committed not to devalue the RMB and
China is acting responsibly as an important member of the
community of nations of the world. Indeed, another round of
devaluation is not helpful to anybody," he stated.
</P>
<P>
Tung arrived in Auckland on Wednesday afternoon from Australia
to start a three-day visit to New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
He will come here on Thursday to meet New Zealand leaders,
including Prime Minister Jenny Shipley, Foreign Minister Don
McKinnon and Finance Minister Bill Birch. He will also attend a
reception to be hosted Thursday night by Chen Wenzhao, Chinese
ambassador to New Zealand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
