<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket closed
higher Wednesday as a firmer Australian dollar cooled concerns
over rising interest rates and pushed major bank shares up.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said investors were confident that Wall Street would
open stronger Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark All Ordinaries Index closed up 24.4 points, or
0.97 percent, at 2549.3, but off its intraday high of 2558.2. It
had reached a low of 2524.9.
</P>
<P>
"As the dollar traded a little better and held its ground, the
talk of a rate rise is slowly disappearing, so we are getting a
little bit of buying in the banks," a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 59.24 U.S. cents, around half a
U.S. cent stronger than the close of 58.68 U.S. cents in Sydney
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Westpac bank led the banks, rising 37 cents, or 3.92 percent,
to 9.82 Australian dollars, followed by ANZ bank gaining 21.8
cents, or 2.1 percent, to 10.618 Australian dollars. Meanwhile,
National Australia Bank climbed 15 cents to 21.5 Australian
dollars and Commonwealth Bank of Australia rose 3 cents to 17.58
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index closed up 37.6 points at 4461.3 and
the All Resources Index 14.5 points higher at 1008.6.
</P>
<P>
Resources giant BHP rose 9.2 cents to 12.77 Australian dollars
while global miner Rio Tinto gained 30 cents, or 1.63 percent, to
18.7 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index closed 13.7 points, or 1.32 percent, higher at
1,052 after New York and Sydney gold bullion prices rose.
</P>
<P>
Sydney trade in gold bullion closed 1.75 U.S. dollars higher at
288.5 U.S. dollars an ounce, after New York gained 3.5 U.S.
dollars to 288.1 U.S. dollars an ounce overnight.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 334.49 million shares valued at 758.27
million U.S. dollars, with rises just pipping falls by 580 to 579
while 467 stocks remained steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
