<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Release of Detainees Hailed in, outside Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The release of nine political
detainees by the Nigerian government Monday has been hailed both
in and outside Nigeria, media reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Human Rights Commission welcomed the move
at a press briefing in Geneva Tuesday and hoped that the Nigerian
government would soon free Moshood Abiola, the widely believed
winner of the annulled June 12, 1993 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. High Commissioner for Human Rights, Mary Robinson,
was pleased to hear of the release of political prisoners,
including General (Olusegun) Obasanjo and she would hope the new
government would soon see a way to release chief Moshood Abiola,"
said John Mills, a rights spokesman for the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU), said in a statement issued Tuesday
from the British Deputy High Commission, Lagos, that "We welcome
General (Abdulsalam) Abubakar's decision to release nine
detainees. This is an important first step in the process of
national reconstruction, reconciliation and development."
</P>
<P>
"We hope that General Abubakar will now move swiftly to effect
a rapid and inclusive transition to c rule,
including detainees. We remain ready to help and support that
process," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government described the release of detainees as an
important step which it hoped would lead to a credible move
toward a democratic government in the west African country.
</P>
<P>
In Nigeria, the National Human Rights Commission commended
General Abubakar over the release of the nine detainees, saying
it looked forward to the full implementation of its
recommendations regarding the detention of persons without trial.
</P>
<P>
The National Democratic Coalition, a major opposition group,
said the release was a first step toward the restoration of the
confidence of Nigerians, as well as the international community.
</P>
<P>
The group, in a statement signed by its deputy leader Abraham
Adesanya, called for the release of all political detainees,
including Abiola, who should be allowed to head a government of
national unity.
</P>
<P>
The most prominent person released by the Nigerian government
Monday is former head of state, General Obasanjo, who was serving
a 15-year jail term for involvement in a failed coup plot in
March 1995.
</P>
<P>
Others are a religious leader, a publisher and leaders of
trade unions and human rights groups.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government said the release is to "facilitate the
process of national reconciliation, reconstruction and successful
completion of the social-political transition program."  
</P>
</TEXT>
