<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Driven High by Yen Strength </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A strong correlation with the
Japanese yen Wednesday brought good news for the Australian dollar
as the struggling Asian unit recovered some ground.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished trading Wednesday at 59.24 U.S.
cents, around half a U.S. cent stronger than the close of 58.68
U.S. cents in Sydney Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It was again the yen that took center stage Wednesday, this
time providing some support for the local unit rather than causing
a fall as on previous days.
</P>
<P>
After touching eight-year lows of above 146 to the U.S. dollar
Tuesday, the Japanese yen closed much stronger at 143.31 against
the greenback.
</P>
<P>
"The yen is just driving everything at the moment," a foreign
exchange trader said.
</P>
<P>
The rise in the yen began offshore Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Economists had suggested that the Australian dollar could fall
to as low as 55 U.S. cents if the yen remained under pressure.
</P>
<P>
Annette Beacher, senior economist with Citibank Australia, said
the upcoming Japanese election would be carefully watched and any
instability in the yen would transfer to the local unit.
</P>
<P>
For Australia, any slowdown in the Japanese economy means less
exports to its largest trading partner, causing the deterioration
of the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
On the cross rates the Australian dollar was also buying 84.9
Japanese yen from 85.52 yen and 1.0642 marks from 1.0588 marks.
</P>
</TEXT>
