<HEADLINE> Dollar Drops Below 142 Yen in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar fell below 142 yen in
Tokyo Wednesday on news that U.S. Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers will visit Japan for high-level talks.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was quoted at 141.98-142.01 yen at 5 p.m. (local time),
down from 142.71-74 yen at 9 a.m., and 143.35-45 yen late Tuesday in
New York.
</P>
<P>
Market players worked on liquidating their overbought dollar
positions for the yen on the expected talks between U.S. and
Japanese monetary officials, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
Expectations that Summers, who is likely to come to Japan Thursday,
will discuss measures with Japanese officials to prevent the yen's
continuing fall arrested the yen's slide, they said.
</P>
<P>
There is also some speculation that the sudden visit is a sign
that the United States will yield to recent political pressure and
help support the falling yen against the dollar, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
But a majority view in financial markets is that Summers is not
coming to Tokyo to discuss coordinated intervention, but to have a
more detailed and probing discussion on how to clean up the
nonperforming loans held by Japanese financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Many traders and analysts said the yen will remain weak against
the dollar over the short term, reflecting differences between the
Japanese and U.S. economies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
