<HEADLINE> South Africa Will Beat Denmark: Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- South Africa head coach
Philippe Troussier vowed to beat Denmark in Thursday's
make-or-break World Cup Group C match after his team lost to
France last week, South African newspapers reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"There are six points left to play for and there is no reason
why we can not win both our remaining matches. I'm very
optimistic," Troussier said in Vichy, France, where the team is
camping.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has to beat both Denmark Thursday and Saudi Arabia
next Wednesday to advance to the next round.
</P>
<P>
Troussier said there would be a change of strategy against
Denmark. "From now on, the finals really start for us. There can
be no more excuses after Denmark," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the French coach said he did not intend to change his
defensive strategy for the match against Denmark. He said the
fault did not lie with his defense in the team's crushing 3-0
defeat to France in their opening fixture played in Marseilles on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We did not lose the game from poor defending. France played
six defensive players against us and I fielded only four. I don't
see the need to make big changes tactically in my defense,"
Troussier said.
</P>
<P>
"We made a mistake in the first half and were punished. We more
than held our own against a very formidable French side for the first
45 minutes," he said, adding that they also made mistakes in the
second half by conceding two goals.
</P>
<P>
Troussier said there could be changes in the team, hinting at a
replacement of the injured striker Phil Masinga by Shaun Bartlett.
</P>
<P>
The coach said the team were disappointed at losing to France,
but would correct their mistakes and beat Denmark.
</P>
<P>
"The pressure is off us now. It hasn't been easy for the
players who've had to adjust (to the World Cup atmosphere). We're
getting there," he said. 
</P>
