<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Foreign Trade Down in First 4 Months of 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Both imports and exports dropped in
Macao in the first four months of this year, the latest official
statistics show.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by the Macao Census and
Statistics Department on Wednesday, exports declined by 6 percent
from the same period last year, to 4.394 billion patacas (about
549.25 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The value of imported goods added up to 4.759 billion patacas
(about 594.875 million dollars), down 7.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
As a result, a trade deficit of 365 million patacas (about
45.625 million dollars) was recorded.
</P>
<P>
Garments and textile goods made up 81 percent of all exports in
the period and their export value declined by 9.2 percent.
Meanwhile, non-textile exports rose by 10.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The United States and the European Union (EU) were the two
leading export markets for Macao and they together bought 73.3
percent of all Macao exported goods. But compared with the same
period last year, purchases made by the United States fell by 1.8
percent and those by the EU by 14.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The decline in imports was attributed to reductions in the
purchase of capital goods, fuel and lubricative oil, raw materials
and semi-finished products and consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
Macao has been hit by an economic slowdown since 1993. Last
year, the growth rate of its gross national product was officially
put at minus 0.1 percent, as against minus 0.3 percent in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
