<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Casino Income Rises 8.4 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Macao Amusement and Tourism Company
(STDM), which monopolizes all casinos in Macao, said its gross
income in 1997 rose 8.4 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
In a report published on Wednesday's Macao Daily News, the STDM
said, however, that its net profit dropped 19.9 percent due to an
increase in casino tax payments and other financial commitments to
the government.
</P>
<P>
The STDM said its net profit for 1997 was 3.71 billion patacas
(about 463.75 million U.S. dollars) and total assets by December
31, 1997, were valued at 28.384 billion patacas (about 3.548
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
It also said the company's hotel and jetfoil businesses
suffered decreases because of fewer passengers as a result of the
financial crisis in the region.
</P>
<P>
But, it said it has confidence in Macao's future and promised
to continue making its contributions to the prosperity and
stability of Macao.
</P>
<P>
The STDM currently runs nine casinos and its subsidiaries run a
jockey club, a greyhound race course and several lotteries in
Macao. It also launched football pools earlier this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
