<HEADLINE> Chinese President Accepts Interview by U.S. Correspondent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
accepted an interview by Elizabeth G. Weymouth, special editor of
U.S. Newsweek and concurrently columnist of Washington Post, at
Zhongnanhai, site of the Central Government, today.
</P>
<P>
Jiang answered her questions on Sino-U.S. relations, the Taiwan
issue, China's entry to WTO, China's role in the Asian financial
crisis and the situation in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on President Bill Clinton's upcoming visit to China,
Jiang said, during his state visit to the United States last year,
President Clinton and himself decided that the two
countries build toward the establishment of a constructive
strategic partnership, which had charted the orientation and
framework for the development of the Sino-U.S. relations into the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the bilateral relations had maintained a good
momentum of continuing improvement and development, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang believed that his successful state visit to the U.S.
last fall and the upcoming state visit by President Clinton would
help further advance the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Qian Qichen was present during the
interview. 
</P>
</TEXT>
