<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Aid Asian Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government Wednesday
decided to provide financial assistance to students from seven
Asian countries hit by economic and financial crisis, Kyodo News
Service reported.
</P>
<P>
The financial aid will be offered to some 6,000 students from
Indonesia, Thailand, South Korea, Malaysia, the Philippines, Laos
and Cambodia, who are studying in Japan at their own expenses, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government has appropriated 3.05 billion yen
(about 21.3 million U.S. dollars) for a scholarship program in the
fiscal 1998 supplementary budget, which is expected to be approved
by the Diet, the Japanese parliament, Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, Japan will give university undergraduate
and graduate students 49,000 yen (about 343 dollars) and 70,000
yen (about 500 dollars) respectively a month from July 1998 to
March 1999.
</P>
<P>
The program is expected to cover 70 percent of students from
the seven countries who are not receiving public or private
scholarships.
</P>
<P>
As of May 1997, there were 51,047 foreign students studying at
Japanese universities, graduate schools and vocational schools, of
which, 45,948, or 90 percent, were from Asia, according to the
Japanese Education Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
