<HEADLINE> EU Pledges Free Trade Pact With S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela has elicited a pledge from European leaders that a
free trade deal between South Africa and the European Union (EU)
will be finalized in three months.
</P>
<P>
Mandela was in Cardiff, Britain, as a guest of an EU summit.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair who chaired the summit,
Tuesday struck an upbeat note on the trade talks, saying only one
percent of trade between South Africa and the EU was still in
dispute, media here reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We have clearly agreed that by the autumn we will have in
place the EU-SA agreement. There have been difficulties to iron
out, actually on both sides, but now we are very close to the
conclusion."
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing Tuesday, Mandela said the International
Monetary Fund supported South Africa's position in trade talks
with the EU. Europe's agricultural subsidies were contributing to
poverty alleviation in Africa, he said.
</P>
<P>
Trade talks between the two sides were deadlocked in April
after the EU refused to make substantial concessions.
</P>
<P>
In the 19th round of negotiations in Brussels, Belgium, held
on June 10 and 11, South Africa presented potential revisions of
its trade offer and some progress was reported.
</P>
<P>
A new round of talks is scheduled for next month in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Mandela met European leaders mainly to bid farewell before his
retirement next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
