<HEADLINE> Nigerian Military Remains Intact, Says Officer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A senior Nigerian officer has
debunked insinuations of widespread disunity in the armed forces
of the country following the death of the late head of state
General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
The rumor was embarrassing and unprogressive, said Federal
Capital Territory Minister Jeremiah Useni, who is currently the
only lieutenant general in the Nigerian military after the head
of state General Abdulsalam Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
"The Nigerian armed forces had been very much in unity and
that unity is still being sustained," said Useni, who until
Tuesday last week was seen as the likely successor to General
Abacha.
</P>
<P>
"Moreover, General Abacha did not die via a coup plot. The
death is a natural one. So there is no reason for anybody to hold
the belief that there is disunity in the armed forces."
</P>
<P>
Useni called on Nigerians to focus on issues that could help
in accelerating task of national building, especially
reconciliation, the Guardian reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"If Nigeria gets destroyed, no one stands to benefit," the
minister warned Tuesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
