<HEADLINE> North China City Using World Bank Loans to Plant Trees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Datong, a major city in north
China's Shanxi Province, is reporting good results in using World
Bank loans to plant trees on barren hills.
</P>
<P>
In 1995 the city began implementing a forest resources
development and protection project financed by the World Bank to
cover 130,000 hectares of barren hills and wasteland.
</P>
<P>
The project, covering seven counties and one district, was to
cost 62 million yuan, 24 million of which would come from local
revenues and other channels, and to focus on 16,000 hectares of
barren hills.
</P>
<P>
To ensure a high survival rate, related areas offered special
training courses to 16,000 technicians, and adopted some
afforestation and drought-resistant technologies. As a result, a
tree survival rate of more than 95 percent was obtained.
</P>
<P>
The city's method has been expanded to other World Bank
projects in 15 areas across the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
