<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder for President Clinton's China Trip: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Xi'an Rich in Culture, Local Flavor (1)
</P>
<P>
XI'AN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Xi'an, reputed as the first city in
the world whose population exceeded one million more than 1,000
years ago, was acclaimed one of the world's four major ancient
capitals with Athens, Cairo and Rome. Xi'an's long history created
a varicolored ancient culture and gave birth to a simple, honest,
generous and unique quality in the local people.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an was known as Chang'an, meaning eternal peace. Numerous
painters living here and their works constituted a major component
part of China's cultural accomplishment. With more emphasis placed
on the reality and livelihood of the people, local painters today,
well-groomed in tradition, have created a new style: the Chang'an
school of Chinese painting.
</P>
<P>
The new style, which originated in the mid 1930s with the rise
of the Red Army, or the Communist-led armed forces in Yan'an, is
noted for its revolutionary ideas but rigorous means of
expression. Many of their works depict the forthright but splendid
northwestern loess plateau and people's hard work. The paintings
are rich in power and grandeur.
</P>
<P>
Shaanxi Opera to the locals is like coffee to the
Europeans. This earliest opera in China, which fathered many other
local operas including Beijing (Peking) Opera, was a combination
of ancient folklore and Chinese traditional royal music.
</P>
<P>
In 1982, several classical plays were for the first time
brought to a foreign stage when they were performed in Japan. The
plays are an interesting and effective way to understand the
people of Shaanxi. The reason is that the opera tells how the
locals feel, many people say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder for President Clinton's China Trip: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Xi'an Rich in Culture, Local Flavor (2)
</P>
<P>
Xi'an is also unique for its numerous bookstores, numbering in
the hundreds. The market lies in the local people's thirsty and
ardent love for books as well as the rapid cultural and
educational development over recent years. Statistics show that
there are 42 institutions of higher learning, and 510 research
institute with 320,000 professional and technical employees in
Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
The city's midnight snacks and refreshments are the local
residents' pride. "Xi'an snacks second to none," as a local saying
goes. With more than 100 varieties, some are hot and spicy while
others are sweet.
</P>
<P>
Because it was once an international metropolis, Xi'an food is
actually a mixture of various flavors from all over the world. Its
longtime foreign residents once reached some 100,000 about ten
centuries ago,
</P>
<P>
Folk art may best represent Xi'an. In Huxian County, almost
every farmer is also a painter. Because of their focus on rural
life and a bulky style, they are called "the school of village
painters." The technical approaches used in paper-cutting,
embroidery, sculpture and other art forms are incorporated into
their paintings. When crops are ripe, they harvest and, at any
other time, they paint.
</P>
<P>
The lantern is an icon of this ancient city. And the best time
to enjoy the symbol is the Lantern Festival, which comes 15 days
after the Spring Festival.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the art of embroidery is a byproduct of the ancient
"Silk Road" to West Asia. China's biggest market for embroidery
products is in Yabai Town in Xi'an's Zhouzhi County. Foreign
visitors frequent it for gifts for family and friends.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
