<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Airport Being Built Next to Jo'burg Int'l </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A three-billion Rand (570
million U.S. dollars) international airport is to be built in
southeast suburb of Johannesburg, local daily Business Report
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The privately owned Springs/Nigel International Airport is
situated on an old airforce base about 20 km southeast of the
city center.
</P>
<P>
The airport is due to be completed within the next five years.
It was expected to generate more than 100 billion Rand (18
billion U.S. dollars) over 20 years and create more than 285,000
jobs, managing director of the chosen developer Braam Loots was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
It will be the second gateway into Gauteng Province, where the
administrative capital of Pretoria and the commercial center of
Johannesburg are situated.
</P>
<P>
Gauteng Province generated 40 percent of the country's gross
domestic product and attracted 80 percent of air traffic movement
in Southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
The airport was designed to cope with future increase in
international air traffic. Johannesburg International Airport was
expected to reach saturation point soon.
</P>
<P>
Intensive research and feasibility studies had shown that
facilities at the Johannesburg International Airport would not be
able to cope with air traffic growth in the next 20 to 30 years.
</P>
<P>
According to Loots, annual passenger flows were expected to
escalate from nine million at Johannesburg International Airport
at present to more than 42 million by 2030.
</P>
<P>
Air traffic movements would increase from 130,000 a year to
more than 700,000 by the same year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Announces Nutrition Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government recently
announced a plan designed to improve the food-supply structure and
nutrition conditions.
</P>
<P>
The first document on nutrition promulgated by the State
Council since 1949, the plan stresses the principle of
"nutrition, hygiene, science and reason" in upholding the eating
traditions of the Chinese nation.
</P>
<P>
According to the document on present nutrition conditions in
China, people in some poverty-stricken areas suffer from
malnutrition due to inadequate food supplies while urban residents
suffer imbalances and over-nutrition.
</P>
<P>
The document calls for people to take vegetable products as the
stable food and animal meat and milk as supplementary.
</P>
<P>
It urges the governments in poor areas to make full use of
local resources in reasonably arranging the production, supply and
distribution of food.
</P>
<P>
Efforts are also called for to scientifically readjust the
structure of food production, and persuade urban residents to form
reasonable eating habits to effectively control chronic
illnesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 08:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OECD Chief Satisfied With Turkey's Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's economy is running
steadily and will gain continued development in the coming years,
said Donald J. Johnston, secretary general of the Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD).
</P>
<P>
"I have the impression that the Turkish government is
determined to reduce the inflation and that the economy is
running well," Johnston was quoted by Wednesday's newspaper
Daily News as saying.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks following his meetings with Turkish Prime
Minister Mesut Yilmaz and other government officials.
</P>
<P>
"Presently, a sound and realistic policy is being
followed. There was no such policy in the past. I see some very
positive improvements in your economy, different in the past,"
Johnston told the paper.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Paris-based financial body is willing to
enhance cooperation with Turkey in various fields.
</P>
<P>
The OECD chief, however, demanded that the Turkish government
take resolute actions in fighting economic crimes, such as money
laundering and corruption, in order to ensure a positive
economic environment.
</P>
<P>
The high inflation rate, which stood at about 68 percent last
year, has been a major bottleneck for Turkey's economic
development over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
However, the figure has decreased since early this year thanks
to a successful monetary plan implemented by the Turkish
government, according to an OECD economic report issued recently.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the inflation in Turkey might continue
its downward trend through next year and fall to 65 percent in
1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
