<HEADLINE> Angola's UNITA Blamed for Re-Capturing Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) has been blamed by the government
for re-capturing five cities and one town.
</P>
<P>
Faustino, head of the Angolan governmental delegation to the
joint commission of Angola peace process, said in Luena City of
eastern Angola's Moxico Province that UNITA has re-controlled
Luau, Lumege-Kameia, Luacano, Alto-Zambeze and Lumbala-Nguimbo
cities and Lacy-Dilolo Town.
</P>
<P>
Muteka said that UN observers and government officials in Luau
and Alto-Zambeze were all detained by UNITA military men.
</P>
<P>
He said that similar incidents happened also in some other
parts of the country, while UNITA military forces were seen on
large-scale manoeuvre in the areas.
</P>
<P>
All the cities and town under UNITA's fresh attacks are those
the opposition force handed over to the government under the
Lusaka Peace Protocol, he said.
</P>
<P>
UNITA handed over 273 of the 353 areas under its control
according to the peace deal, but refused to back out from central
Angola's "sensitive areas" like Bailundo and Andulo.  
</P>
</TEXT>
