<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lancang River: New Source for China to Develop Hydropower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Lancang River, known as the
oriental Danube, is becoming China's new source for hydropower
generation. Eight power stations will be built on the river in the
next 30 years.
</P>
<P>
The Dachao Mountain Hydropower Station, now under construction,
will be installed with a capacity of 1.35 million kilowatts (kw)
and should be completed in 2003.
</P>
<P>
It will be China's first share-holding power station with a
capacity of more than one million kw and will provide more than 7
billion kilowatts/hour (kwh) of electricity annually. Since
the 1980s, the state has spent 6 billion yuan developing
hydropower resources of the Lancang.
</P>
<P>
The first one-million-kw hydro-electric power station along the
river was at Manwan, built in the early 1980s, with a capacity of
1.5 million kw. It was financed by the central and local
governments.
</P>
<P>
Preparations are also being made for another two million-kw
stations, construction of which will start in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The river is estimated to have the capacity of generating more
than 100 billion kwh annually, accounting for one-fourth of the
province's total.
</P>
<P>
Some Southeast Asian nations will be confronted with
electricity shortages during the first half of the 21st century,
experts said, adding that power development along the river will
not only provide electricity to other parts of China, but also to
neighboring countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
