<HEADLINE> Dutch Insurer Join Hands With China Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- ING Insurance, a member of the ING
Group of the Netherlands, has funded the establishment of a LOMA
(Life Office Management Association of the United States)
Training and Examination Center at the Graduated School of the
People's Bank of China (PBOC).
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed by the two sides here today, ING
Insurance will donate 500,000 yuan to set up the center in
Beijing. This will be the third LOMA examination center that ING
Insurance has sponsored in China.
</P>
<P>
LOMA holds 100,000 examinations of Fellow of Life Insurance
Management Institute (FLMI) in more than 60 countries in the world
every year.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, more than 800 persons took the FLMI examination in
China.
</P>
<P>
Thomas Donaldson, president and chief executive officer of
LOMA, said at the signing ceremony that China is expected to have
one of the largest groups taking FLMI examinations in the next
five years. It is expected to rank second or third in the world,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Donaldson said the translation of the examination papers is
under way and that people can take FLMI examinations in Chinese
beginning in January.
</P>
<P>
Gan Peigen, honorary president of the PBOC Graduate School,
said that establishment of the LOMA centers is one of the steps
that China took to upgrade its financial and banking systems to
international standards.
</P>
<P>
Phillip Sherriff, chief executive officer and a member of the
executive committee of ING Financial Services International Asia,
said at the signing ceremony that ING Insurance is actively
involved in China's efforts to develop a social security system,
reform its housing system and improve the education system.
</P>
<P>
Sherriff expressed the hope that ING Insurance will soon obtain
government approval to do business in China so that it will
contribute more to the country's reform and opening drive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
