<HEADLINE> Estrada Asks Critics Not to Fuss Over Marcos Burial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President-Elect Joseph
Estrada Wednesday urged his critics not to make an issue out of
the proposed burial of former President Ferdinand Marcos at the
heroes' cemetery in Manila.
</P>
<P>
Estrada made the appeal to those opposing the burial of Marcos'
remains as he assured them that the criminal and other cases filed
against the Marcoses will still be pursued by the government.
</P>
<P>
Burying the former president, he said, would only mean that the
government is committed to according the dead the rightful
Christian burial.
</P>
<P>
Instead, Estrada urged his critics to focus on more pressing
concerns, particularly the problems of the economy, peace and
order and the country's foreign and domestic debt.
</P>
<P>
Estrada agreed to bury Marcos at the heroes' cemetery on July
11 after he assumes the presidency. However, Marcos would not be
granted a state funeral.
</P>
<P>
Several organizations recently launched a signature drive in
the hope of convincing Estrada to change his mind. The opponents
include former President Corazon Aquino.
</P>
<P>
Marcos fled to Hawaii, the United States, in a popular revolt
in 1986 and died there three years later. His remains were brought
back to the country in 1993 for a private funeral in his native
province of Ilocos Norte. 
</P>
</TEXT>
