<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia, Angola Seal Landmines Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Zambia and Angola have agreed to
cooperate in removing the landmines that still litter 1500
kilometers of the two countries' common border.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed here Tuesday by foreign affairs minister
Keli Walubita when arriving at the Lusaka international airport
after a five-day visit to Angola, Times of Zambia reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister told reporters that landmines planted
many years ago continue to be a major source of insecurity
especially in areas along the two neibouring countries' common
border.
</P>
<P>
He said that there is no meaningful development along the
common border if insecurity prevails.
</P>
<P>
"We discussed the area of landmines planted years back along
the border. So we will work together and ensure that a de-mining
program is jointly pursued by the two countries," said Walubita.
</P>
<P>
He added that the two countries are signatories to the
Montreal Protocol on Landmines and will approach donors to help
them put their de-mining program in place.
</P>
<P>
Zambia and Angola have also agreed to rehabilitate the
Bengwela railway to enhance bilateral economic cooperation and
trade, according to Walubita. The Bengwela railway which connects
with the railway in the Democratic Republic of Congo is a main
transportation trunk in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said economic experts will soon meet to rehabilitate the
railway which has been discussed since the conflicts in Angola
started several decades ago.
</P>
<P>
Zambia and Angola have also agreed to revive their joint
permanent commission which because of the situation in that
country has been idle since 1989 when it was formed, stated
Walubita. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
