<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Grain Marketing System Continues to Mature (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, June 17 (Xinhua) -- In a seven-storey building in
central China's Zhengzhou City, nervous traders from throughout
China are painstakingly monitoring data on a hall's 100-odd
computers.
</P>
<P>
It is the Zhengzhou Grain Wholesale Market, the first and
largest such kind in China where close to ten percent, or three
million tons of grain and five billion yuan worth of cereals,
cooking oil, by-products and fodder circulated nationwide are
traded annually.
</P>
<P>
The wholesale grain market system offers appealing prospects
for members of China's agricultural sector which demonstrates that
China's grain marketing system has continued to mature, said an
expert from the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
It enables the Chinese government to implement macro-controls
on the national grain system. Related efforts are vitally
important to national economic growth and livelihood of Chinese
people, he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides the spot market established in 1990, the Zhengzhou
Market also set up a futures market in May 1993.
</P>
<P>
The aforementioned markets, which coexist and promote each
other, have developed into a national information and trade center
for cereals and cooking oil. Chinese and foreign economists refer
to the highly successful market as the "Zhengzhou Model".
</P>
<P>
"A major objective of ongoing reform of China's grain marketing
system is to find scientific mechanisms governing grain prices. A
wholesale grain market system, an integral part of the mechanism,
has taken shape in Zhengzhou," according to Li Jingmou, chairman
of the Zhengzhou Wholesale Market.
</P>
<P>
China, a nation with a population of over 1.2 billion people,
has long pursued a policy under which state grain companies engage
in a unified effort to purchase farm produce in line with fixed
quotas. The government grants several billion yuan annually to
offset the losses of related companies which have for many years
suffered from bad debts and financial losses resulting from
redundant staffs, high operational costs and poor economic returns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Grain Marketing System Continues to Mature (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bumper harvests make it difficult for farmers to sell grain in
bumper years and crop failures lead to soaring prices.
</P>
<P>
China's grain marketing system has taken a great step forward
towards market-oriented operation.
</P>
<P>
Ding Shengjun, deputy director of the Commercial and Economic
Research Center under the State Internal Trade Bureau, said: "The
Zhengzhou Grain Wholesale Market is a product of grain marketing
system reform. The market has successfully experimented with grain
marketing in China."
</P>
<P>
Pricing is the core of the market system, with the grain price
index offered by the Zhengzhou Market providing the basis for
related reform, according to Ding Shengjun, a grain marketing
expert who has worked in the field for many decades,
</P>
<P>
Substantial national grain reserves has made it possible for
China to regulate its grain market. Facts prove that the gap
between bumper harvests and crop failure most often ranges from
15-25 million tons. Ding noted that the goal for stabilizing grain
prices applies to only a small portion of the national grain
reserve.
</P>
<P>
He Ruo, director of Fuzhou Grain Wholesale Market, said in a
telephone interview, that her province is one of China's leading
grain production bases and is linked to the Zhengzhou computer
network. She added that the link enables the province to receive
information and release trade prices on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin Municipal Grain Bureau established links with the
network in 1996 and over a dozen provinces including leading grain
producers such as Heilongjiang, Guangdong, Hunan and Hubei are
expected to join in the near future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0200 </DOCNO>
