<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 07:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Butler Urges Iraq to Cooperate with UNSCOM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Chief U.N. arms inspector
Richard Butler has called on Iraq to cooperate with the United
Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) to help end its mission
quickly.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference held here late Tuesday, Butler
said he promised Iraq that UNSCOM would do its work "honestly,
confidently and quickly, we have no hidden agenda, we want
disarmament."
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM is charged with overseeing the elimination of Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction, which was ordered by U.N. Security
Council after the end of the 1991 Gulf War triggered by Iraq's
invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Butler said that if Iraq cooperates with UNSCOM according to
a program of work, things are expected to be "quite different."
</P>
<P>
He reached an agreement on the program Sunday with the Iraqi
government for arms inspections in the next two months, raising
hope that Iraq is close to being free from U.N. economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed the sanctions on Iraq in 1990
after its invasion of Kuwait. It will not lift the sanctions
unless UNSCOM certifies that Iraq has destroyed the banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
"What we need for successful completion (of the arms
inspections) is full cooperation by Iraq," Butler said.
</P>
<P>
"We think we could do it in two months because Iraq did
promise the (U.N.) Secretary General (Kofi Annan) a new level of
cooperation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan reached an agreement with Iraq in February, under which a
special U.N. team conducted free and unrestrictive inspections of
Iraq's eight presidential compounds, which used to be off-limits.
</P>
<P>
Butler, who arrived here Monday, has held a wide-range of
talks with Kuwaiti leaders and briefed them on the outcome of his
five-day visit to Iraq from last Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian Province Adopts Fishing Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A prolonged fishing ban started
Tuesday in east China's Fujian Province to protect marine
resources.
</P>
<P>
The three-month ban, replacing the former two-month one, will
end Sept. 15, according to the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
Trawlers and net catches by sailboats will be prohibited until
then in the sea north of 26 degrees north latitude, according to
officials.
</P>
<P>
Similar bans will also be adopted from June 16 to Aug. 15 in
the area from 26 degrees north latitude to 24 degrees 30 minutes
north latitude.
</P>
<P>
In the northern part of the province from the boundary with
Zhejiang Province to Beijiao, the ban will last two months from
May 16 to July 15; and in the central part in an area from Beijiao
to Weitou, the ban starts May 1 and ends June 30.
</P>
<P>
China has adopted such a ban for three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
