<HEADLINE> Xiamen as Seen Through Foreigners' Eyes (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Martijn C. Notten, general manager
of the Dutch-funded Xiamen Paktank Co. Ltd. in the special
economic zone, said he appreciates his Chinese employees very
much. Notten expressed his hope that his post will be filled by his
Chinese counterparts in the near future.
</P>
<P>
"They are competent to take the responsibility," said
Notten. "They are young, but they are very proficient in their own
fields."
</P>
<P>
John T.M Chi, manager of Taikoo (Xiamen) Aircraft Engineering
Co. Ltd., expressed similar opinion about his Chinese workers. The
firm, engaged in airplane maintenance, primarily serves foreign
customers. Chi said his firm pays great attention to the foreign
language level of employees as well as their knowledge of the
world outside China.
</P>
<P>
"In Xiamen, this does not pose a problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
The high quality of personnel is considered an important
advantage for attracting foreign investors, said Shi Zhaobin, a
high-ranking official in the city in east China's Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
So far, 10.4 percent of the city's population has obtained a
college degree.
</P>
<P>
"Though different investors have different requests, Xiamen can
really provide them all they want," said Shi.
</P>
<P>
Besides advantages in personnel, the city has a favorable
geographic position, an advanced infrastructure, and services and
management comparable to the international norm.
</P>
<P>
It is after careful comparison that the Dutch-funded Paktank
chose Xiamen as its settlement site. "Xiamen, having a deep-water
port and being advantageously located, has great potential for
further development," said Notten.
</P>
</TEXT>
