<HEADLINE> Xiamen as Seen Through Foreigners' Eyes (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The efficient sea port and airport in Xiamen have also solved
Taikoo's problems for transporting large equipment and tools for
airplane maintenance, said Chi.
</P>
<P>
Chi said his firm is considering a third-phase project, though
their second one is just under way.
</P>
<P>
A Philippine investor said he has not been as fortunate as his
Dutch and Hong Kong counterparts. Though his investment contract
was postponed because of the depreciation of the Philippine Peso,
he believed Xiamen the best place for investment.
</P>
<P>
The investor said he was moved by the sincere help from
officials in the Supervision Commission of the Haichang
Investment Zone. When many investors were mired in the Southeast
Asian financial crisis, the commission adopted supporting policies
to help them, he said.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland-based ABB Corp. has increased its number of
branches in Xiamen to four, lured by the high profits of its first
one. It also bought 10,000 square meters to build plants, changing
its original policy of not investing in real estate projects.
</P>
<P>
By the end of April, the city had used 8.12 billion
U.S. dollars for 4,366 projects.
</P>
<P>
While investors come to Xiamen for its favorable investment
environment, foreigners working here are attracted by the cozy
living.
</P>
<P>
"There's no difference living here than in our own country,"
said Gerold Brunken, financial controller of the ABB Xiamen Switch
Gear Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Brunken described the climate as spring-like in all four
seasons, and said he liked the beautiful island scene, safe social
security, convenient transportation and clean air.
</P>
<P>
As many foreigners now living here know, Xiamen has been named
China's hygiene city, park city, and environmental protection
city, all set by the state to show the city's advancement. 
</P>
