<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Phone Boom in Africa Predicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Africa could see a boom in the
number of phone lines across the continent early next century,
but rural areas still look set to miss out, international experts
predict.
</P>
<P>
New satellite, cellular and fiber optics technology could see
a rapid rise in phone lines in many African cities and large
towns as costs become lower and state-owned phone firms become
more efficient once privatized, the Daily Nation newspaper
Wednesday quoted a report in World Bank News as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Africa is on the move and telecommunications is one of the
sectors leading the way," said World Bank's telecommunications
expert Paul Bermingham.
</P>
<P>
"Not only have we seen a revolution in technology, but there's
been a wave of reforms and private financing sweeping through
Africa, which is opening up the telecommunications sector," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Although Africa makes up around 12 percent of the world's
population, it currently only has 1.8 percent of the world's
phone lines, said the report.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, nine Sub-Saharan African countries have
privatized their state-run telephone companies, representing
about 75 percent of all telephone lines in the region.
</P>
<P>
Another 12 African states, including Kenya, are planning
similar privatizations.
</P>
<P>
The report says that while telephone lines in sub-Saharan
Africa are still expensive, the cost per line has dropped
dramatically in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
However, the report acknowledges there are still huge problems
getting phone lines into the rural areas because of the cost
involved.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0209 </DOCNO>
