<HEADLINE> Statistics Show Tibetans Have More Comfortable Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- An Australian student studying at
Tibet University said that he never thought that Tibetans lived
such a comfortable life until he started school in Lhasa.
</P>
<P>
"What surprised me most is that I can choose TV programs
through 30 channels in Lhasa," he said.
</P>
<P>
Actually, many local residents agree with his conclusion that
they now enjoy a colorful cultural life.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics show that, at present, for each 100 urban
households in the Tibet Autonomous Region there are 88 color TV
sets and six black-and-white TVs.
</P>
<P>
Local residents also have enriched their diets with
improvements in their material life.
</P>
<P>
According to related statistics, the per capita meat
consumption in Lhasa is 50 kilograms a year, up 50 percent from
1991. Drastic increases have also been reported in the consumption
of edible oil, sugar, eggs and milk products.
</P>
<P>
At present, the annual per capita income of urban Lhasa
residents stands at 620 U.S. dollars. Some 50 percent of local
families have refrigerators; 46 percent have cameras; 42 percent
have washing machines; and more than 80 percent use liquefied gas,
electric stoves or solar energy to cook their meals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
