<HEADLINE> Military, MILF Rebels Clash in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Government troops and Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF) rebels renewed their clashes in the
southern Philippines, sending hundreds of civilians fleeing their
villages.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines News Agency reported Wednesday that both sides
started shelling early Tuesday and went on the whole day pounding
each other with mortar fire in Buldon, Maguindanao province.
</P>
<P>
Civilians living in at least five villages were forced to flee
to safe ground, the report said, adding that the parties accused
each other of "firing the first shot."
</P>
<P>
Rosque Garingalao, spokesman of the Army's Sixth Infantry
Division, reported no casualties on the military. He confirmed the
evacuation of civilians but refused to give specifics, saying the
troops assigned to Buldon will continue looking over the safety of
civilians.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Al Haj Murad, MILF vice chairman for military
affairs, chided the military for starting the renewed hostilities.
</P>
<P>
He said the military fired at least five 105 howitzer rounds
and 19 mortar rounds, but killed none of the MILF members.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, currently the largest rebel group in the country,
often clashes with the military although it has been engaged in
low-level peace talks with the government. 
</P>
