<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Tea Production Hits New High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Global tea production rose by 1.3
percent in 1997 to reach its highest level ever, according to
preliminary estimates released by the International Tea Committee
(ITC).
</P>
<P>
The estimates put 1997 world output at 2.652 million tons,
compared with the previous record of 2.617 million in 1996, the
East African Standard newspaper quoted the survey as reporting
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In its latest statistical bulletin, the ITC, which represents
the tea industry in the main exporting and importing countries,
reported that both India and Sri Lanka brought in record crops
last year.
</P>
<P>
But Kenyan production, which was hit by drought in the first
quarter, was sharply down on 1996's record figure.
</P>
<P>
Indian production in 1997 was 810,613 tons, compared with
780,034 tons in 1996, Sri Lankan production was 277,428 tons
compared with 258,969 tons and Kenyan production was 220,722 tons
compared with 257,162 tons in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Other 1997 tea yield figures (in tons, with 1996 comparisons
in brackets) include China 613,366 (593,386), Indonesia 119,900
(144,000), Turkey 110,000 (114,540), Japan 91,205 (88,709), Iran
60,000 (58,000), Argentina 55,000 (43,000), Bangladesh 53,495
(53,406), Vietnam 42,000 (40,000), Malawi 43,930 (38,312),
Tanzania 22,475 (19,768) and Uganda 21,075 (17,418).
</P>
<P>
World exports of tea in 1997 totaled 1.156 million tons,
compared with 1.115 million in 1996, according to the ITC.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka ranked as the largest tea exporter in the world last
year with a tea exportation of 257,678 tons, followed by China
(202,464 tons), India (200,657 tons) and Kenya (194,024 tons),
said the ITC.
</P>
<P>
Global net tea imports (after excluding re-exports) stood at
1.135 million tons in 1997, up from 1.117 million tons in the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Britain was the biggest tea importer last year with 150,538
tons (148,452 tons in 1996), followed by Russia with 150,000 tons
(111.095 tons in 1996). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
