<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Records More Overseas Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's total overseas
debt reached 99 billion New Zealand dollars (49.5 billion U.S.
dollars) at the end of March this year, Statistics New Zealand
announced in a press release received on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The latest figure represents a rise of 19.4 billion dollars
(9.7 billion U.S. dollars), or 24 percent, since March 1997. It is
also 41 percent higher than the figure in March 1995.
</P>
<P>
The office said the ratio of New Zealand's total overseas debt
to GDP now stands at 100.4 percent, the highest since it began to
publish the series on debt in December 1992.
</P>
<P>
The mounting debt has been caused by growing borrowing by the
corporate sector, which has increased by 20.1 billion dollars (10
billion U.S. dollars) since December 1992 to 79 billion dollars
(39.5 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
At the same time, official sector overseas debt has been
gradually falling, from 26.3 billion dollars (13.2 billion U.S.
dollars) in March 1994 to 20 billion dollars (10 billion U.S.
dollars) in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
In the past year, official overseas debt dropped by 700 million
dollars (350 million U.S. dollars), the press release said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
