<HEADLINE> Handcrafted Pewter Medals to Be Awarded at </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Winners at the Kuala Lumpur
Commonwealth Games will be rewarded with medals made of pewter,
the traditional Malaysian alloy, and plated with gold, silver and
bronze, Games organizers said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Each of the 1,340 handcrafted medals weighs 120 grams, is 60
millimeters in diameter and 6 millimeters in thickness, said the
manufacturers, the Royal Selangor Pewter Factory.
</P>
<P>
Sculptured on the medals are Kuala Lumpur's five main landmarks
-- the colonial High Court building, Parliament House, the
National Monument, the television tower and the 88-story Petronas
twin towers, the world's tallest building.
</P>
<P>
Hashim Ali, the chief of the 1998 games organizing committee,
said: "The medals are an excellent creative reflection of our
country."
</P>
<P>
The medals had been handcrafted by a group of artisans chosen
from among the factory's 500 workers.
</P>
<P>
Pewter, an alloy of tin, copper and antimony, is widely used in
crafting expensive vases, tankards, decorative tumblers and
jewelry.
</P>
<P>
More than 4,000 athletes from 68 nations are competing in the
10-day games that start from September 11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
