<HEADLINE> Overseas Pakistanis Respond to Self-Reliance Fund: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said here Wednesday that overseas Pakistanis responded
enthusiastically to his call for increasing remittances to their
native country for meeting economic challenges.
</P>
<P>
Talking to the media at Islamabad Airport on his return from a
four-day visit to Britain, Sharif said overseas Pakistanis are
fully charged and want to strengthen Pakistan economically in the
wake of the nuclear detonation.
</P>
<P>
He termed as highly successful his visit, which was aimed at
motivating overseas Pakistanis to increase home remittances for
achieving self-reliance.
</P>
<P>
Pakistanis residing in Britain have assured him that they would
contribute generously to Pakistan's self-reliance fund, Sharif
said.
</P>
<P>
The fund was launched by the prime minister shortly after
Pakistan's nuclear tests in May. Sharif has expressed the hope
that each and every earning member of the Pakistani family
residing abroad would remit at least 1,000 U.S. dollars every year
through nationalized banks.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question, Sharif said his meeting with British
Deputy Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs Derek Fatchett on
Tuesday was good.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Sharif said, he was informed that the
British government considers the Kashmir issue as the main cause
of tension in South Asia and that major powers are ready to help
Pakistan resolve the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
