<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Keeps Budget Deficit Under Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese government has made
significant progress in controlling its ballooning budget deficit
below the overall 1998 target of 42 percent in the past five
months this year, the Daily Star newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The deficit for the first five months averaged 35 percent
after the government collected 1.229 billion U.S. dollars in
revenue and spent 1.905 billion dollars, the paper quoted the
Finance Ministry's monthly report as saying.
</P>
<P>
The expenditure is expected to reach 5.224 billion U.S. dollars
with revenues projected at 3.042 billion dollars this year, the
paper added.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit has exceeded 50 percent since 1994 and
reached the record high of 59 percent last year, overshooting the
target of 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
An official at the Finance Ministry said that the rise in
revenue was due to the 2 percent increase in customs duty
imposed at the end of April and the inflow of income tax.
</P>
<P>
"We're confident we shall remain below target. We've taken
revenue measures, expenditure cuts and we have a political
consensus in the country," the Finance Ministry said in the
report.
</P>
<P>
Ghaleb Musleh, a senior manager at the central bank, said that
the new figures were a result of better revenue collection and
increased taxes, but they also reflected a certain amount of
window dressing by the government.
</P>
<P>
"We can't deny that there was a big effort to improve the
fiscal position, but the May figures do not show the true budget
balance and expenditure for 1998," Musleh said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
