<HEADLINE> Eastern Chinese City's Environment Protection in Rural Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANTAI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The city of Yantai in east China's
Shandong Province now has some 30 environmental protection
organizations in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Yantai's rural economy has developed rapidly since 1978, with
township-owned enterprises growing at 30 percent annually, to
100,000.
</P>
<P>
They had 98.7 billion yuan worth of industrial output in 1997,
accounting for 74.2 percent of the city's total. But, they have
also caused pollution. So, to protect the rural environment,
Yantai has tried to build environmental protection organizations
each staffed by three to five workers, since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Laizhou, a suburb of Yantai, has six rural environmental
protection organizations, which have discovered at least 100
instances of damage to the environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyans Face Two Years of Pain: Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Kenyans face two years of
economic pain even if the government implements a wide-ranging
and long-overdue reform program, Micah Cheserem, Governor of the
country's central bank, has warned.
</P>
<P>
However, there is no alternative if the government is to avoid
an even-deeper crisis, Cheserem was quoted by Wednesday's Daily
Nation newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The economy is like a ship -- it will not just change
course," he said Tuesday," But the determination is there."
</P>
<P>
"There has to be pain before gain.... We will have to go
through pain for perhaps two years, but it is for the good of the
country," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he hailed Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae's agenda
for reform, announced in last Thursday's draft budget.
</P>
<P>
In his budget speech, Nyachae said he wanted to balance the
budget in fiscal 1998/99 (July/June) after running a deficit of
around 2.7 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) in 1997/98.
</P>
<P>
Faced with a growing mountain of short-term domestic debt and
cripplingly high interest rates, Nyachae says government spending
and civil service jobs must be slashed.
</P>
<P>
Cheserem said the changes proposed in Nyachae's budget speech
will face opposition from strong vested interests within the
government itself.
</P>
<P>
"For the public good these people had better accept to let
go," he said, "They have to let go because the situation is
precarious."
</P>
<P>
The economy has slowed to standstill this year with interest
rates of more than 25 percent on the government's three-month
treasury bills choking off private investment.
</P>
<P>
Cheserem said that he believed interest rates would fall if
the government puts its promises into practice and investor
confidence returns.
</P>
<P>
An expected return of International Monetary Fund (IMF)
support this year would be a major factor in bringing rates down,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Last July's decision by the IMF to halt a key loan package on
the grounds of poor governance and corruption was the spark for a
flight of international capital and an increase in treasury bill
rates to 26 percent from 18.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
