<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Major Events in Sino-U.S. Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The following is a list of major
events in Sino-United States relations from 1972 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
February 21-28, 1972: Then U.S. President Richard Nixon paid an
official visit to China, during which a Sino-U.S. joint communique
was issued in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
May 1, 1973: The liaison offices set up by China and the United
States in each other's capital started functioning.
</P>
<P>
December 1-5, 1975: Then U.S. President Gerald Ford visited
China.
</P>
<P>
December 16, 1978: China and the United States issued a joint
communique which called for the establishment of diplomatic
relations between the two countries on January 1, 1979.
</P>
<P>
January 1, 1979: China and the United States formally
established diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
January 28-February 5, 1979: Then Chinese Vice-Premier Deng
Xiaoping paid an official visit to the United States, during which
two agreements were signed on scientific, technological and
cultural cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
April 10, 1979: Then U.S. President Jimmy Carter signed the
Taiwan Relations Act.
</P>
<P>
July 7, 1979: The Chinese and the U.S. governments signed in
Beijing the Sino-U.S. Agreement on Trade Relations which stipulated
that the two countries mutually enjoy most favored nation status.
</P>
<P>
December 31, 1979: The United States abrogated the Mutual
Defense Treaty, signed with Taiwan in 1954, and the six affiliated
agreements.
</P>
<P>
August 17, 1982: The Chinese and the U.S. governments issued a
joint communique under which the United States promised to
gradually reduce its sales of weapons to Taiwan until the complete
settlement of the problem.
</P>
<P>
April 26-May 1, 1984: Then U.S. President Ronald Reagon visited
China, during which the two countries signed four agreements on
avoiding double-taxation and tax evasion and initialed an
agreement on cooperation on the peaceful use of nuclear energy.
</P>
<P>
July 22-31, 1985: Then Chinese President Li Xiannian visited
the United States, the first by a Chinese head of state since the
founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
February 25-26, 1989: Then U.S. President George Bush paid a
working visit to China.
</P>
<P>
May 22-23, 1989: Wan Li, the then chairman of the Standing
Committee of China's National People's Congress, visited the
United States.
</P>
<P>
January 31, 1992: Former Chinese Premier Li Peng held talks
with then U.S President George Bush while attending a summit of
the United Nations Security Council in New York.
</P>
<P>
November 19, 1993: Chinese President Jiang Zemin held talks
with U.S. President Bill Clinton during the informal Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation (APEC) leadership meeting in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
May 26, 1994: U.S. President Bill Clinton declared an extension
of the most favored nation (MFN) status for China, and delinked
the issue of human rights to the provision of the MFN status.
</P>
<P>
October 3-4, 1994: Then Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen visited the United States. Qian and then
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher signed two joint
communiques on stopping production of the military use nuclear
fission material and on the issue of missile proliferation.
</P>
<P>
November 14, 1994: Chinese President Jiang Zemin, on the
sidelines of attending an informal APEC leadership meeting in
Bogor, met U.S. President Bill Clinton in Jakarta and put forward
the Five Principles for the establishment of a new type of
Sino-U.S. relationship.
</P>
<P>
October 24, 1995: Chinese President Jiang Zemin met President
Bill Clinton in New York while attending the special conference
held for marking the 50th anniversary of the founding of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
November 24, 1996: Chinese President Jiang Zemin met U.S.
President Bill Clinton at an informal APEC leadership meeting in
Manila.
</P>
<P>
February 24, 1997: U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
visited China.
</P>
<P>
March 24-28, 1997: U.S. Vice President Albert Gore visited
China.
</P>
<P>
March 27-30, 1997: Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives
Newt Gingrich visited China.
</P>
<P>
April 28-30, 1997: Then Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen visited the United States.
</P>
<P>
October 26-November 3, 1997: Chinese President Jiang Zemin paid
a state visit to the United States, the first by a Chinese
president in 12 years. A joint communique, issued on October 29,
called on the two countries to strengthen cooperation and strive
for the establishment of a constructive strategic partnership
oriented to the 21st century, in a bid to promote world peace and
development.
</P>
<P>
November 24, 1997: Chinese President Jiang Zemin met with U.S.
President Bill Clinton at an informal APEC leadership meeting in
Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
January 17-19, 1998: U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen
visited China. An agreement on establishing a consultation
mechanism to strengthen maritime military safety was signed
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
March 14, 1998: The United States announced that it would not
support the presentation of a human rights bill against China at
the U.N. conference on human rights in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
March 19, 1998: The United States declared that the
U.S.-Chinese Agreement on Cooperation on the Peaceful Use of
Nuclear Energy, which had been in dormancy for 13 years, came into
force.
</P>
<P>
April 29-May 1, 1998: U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright visited China. An agreement was signed between the two
countries on the establishment of a direct secure telephone link.
</P>
</TEXT>
