<HEADLINE> Gas-Based Industries Planned for Northern Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government plans to
establish natural gas-based industries in the country's northern
region, English dailies here reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed Tuesday by Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina in
her written replies to a question raised in the parliament as she
was in New Delhi on a visit.
</P>
<P>
"The government is actively considering to set up urea
fertilizer factories and light engineering complexes with the
availability of natural gas in the northern region or studying
feasibility of gas supply from the eastern region," she told the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The government would also give importance to arrangement of
financial allocation for setting up such industries in the region,
she added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the issue of environmental protection, she said,
"This matter would surely get top priority in setting up any
industry which should be friendly to the environment in the area."
</P>
<P>
"Private entrepreneurs will be encouraged in this regard" and
parliament members could set up industries in the region, she
stated.
</P>
<P>
The government had incorporated various projects of different
sectors in the budget for 1998-99 keeping in view the development
in the northern region, she said.
</P>
<P>
The government was pledge-bound to ensure balanced development
in all areas of the country and remove any discrimination to help
Bangladesh emerge as a prosperous country, she stressed.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is rich in natural gas reserves which are estimated
by some experts at about 80 trillion cubic feet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
