<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Foreign Debt Declining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's foreign debt dropped by
4 billion U.S. dollars to 86 billion dollars in the second quarter
of this year, according to the latest figure released by the
Central Bank Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The country's total foreign debt stood at 90 billion dollars in
the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
About 83 percent of Thailand's foreign debt was presently being
rolled over by creditors, Central Bank Governor Chatumongol
Sonakul said.
</P>
<P>
"The rollover rate by foreign creditors is pretty good. Of the
total debt rolled over, about 90 percent is voluntary, while the
rest stems from the inability of local firms to repay,"
Chatumongol said.
</P>
<P>
He said it was a positive sign that total foreign debt was
declining and that short-term debt was being restructured with
longer maturities.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's total short-term debt, due within one year, is about
20 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
