<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Mission to Promote Trade Hailed a Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 17 (Xinhua) -- An eleven-day three-nation trade
mission led by Thai Deputy Commerce Minister Photipong Lamsam has
successfully secured new markets for Thai products, the Bangkok
Post Wednesday quoted the Department of Export Promotion (DEP) as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The mission also secured raw material supplies for Thailand's
gem and jewelry industry, which is battling with a shortage of raw
materials, DEP said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Comprising leading businessmen from the Board of Trade and Thai
Gems and Jewelry Trade Association, the mission visited South
Africa, Brazil and Italy between June 4 and 15.
</P>
<P>
The export target for Thailand's gems and jewelry industry this
year is 2.03 billion U.S. dollars. By the end of the first
quarter, the industry had reached 17.6 percent of its target.
</P>
<P>
In South Africa, the mission held negotiations with local gems
and jewelry association to purchase raw materials at favorable
prices. The association also said it would participate in
Thailand's annual gem and jewelry fairs.
</P>
<P>
Members of South Africa's Board of Trade expressed interest in
buying Thai goods, especially electrical transformers, machinery,
foods, furniture and garments, and plan to send a buying mission
to Thailand by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
In Brazil, the mission held talks with the Brazilian minister
who is in charge of industry, trade and tourism to expand
bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
Thailand hopes to use Brazil as a gateway to Latin American
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilians said they were interested in purchasing Thai
gems and jewelry, fragrant jasmine rice, medical gloves, rubber
block and latex, synthetic fiber and fishing equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
