<HEADLINE> Bulls' Assistant Coach Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, Jue 16 (Xinhua) -- Chicago Bulls assistant coach
Jimmy Rodgers resigned Tuesday, sending a signal that this could
be the end for the six-time NBA champion team.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came only a few hours after coach Phil Jackson
told a celebration rally that this was his last season.
</P>
<P>
Rodgers said it was time to step back and evaluate his
future. The assistant coach, 55, was one of four assistants under
Jackson this season.
</P>
<P>
Rodgers is a 27-year NBA veteran who has been with the Bulls
for the past three years. He also was an assistant, player
personnel director and coach in Boston when the Celtics win three
titles.
</P>
<P>
Rodgers, who also coached with the Cleveland Cavaliers and
Minnesota Timberwolves, started his coaching career at North
Dakota after graduating from Iowa.
</P>
<P>
"We hate to lose Jimmy. He's an outstanding coach and an even
better person. We will miss him," general manager Jerry Krause
said. 
</P>
