</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Finance Minister Pledges to Cut Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Thai Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmanhaeminda said he would try to reduce the country's high
interest rates, which have caused liquidity problems in the real
sector, the Bangkok Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"I'd be happy to see interest rates at around 11-15 percent to
ease liquidity," Tarrin said at the cabinet meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Interest rates in Thai commercial banks are between 16 to 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
But the finance minister made it clear that a cut would not
come soon as regional currency volatility made it necessary to
maintain a high interest rate regime.
</P>
<P>
The baht would be the first to be hit by the regional
fluctuations, but the emergency loan plan should cushion the
impact, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin had already asked for additional loans from the
International Monetary Fund, Japan and the United States to
augment international reserves if the crisis hit again.
</P>
<P>
He said measures would also have to be worked out to give the
country immunity from financial ills such as those concerning debt
restructuring and capital increases.
</P>
<P>
The government needed to speed the use of the 1998 budget to
improve liquidity and create more jobs, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, at the cabinet meeting, Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
said the recent turmoil, featured by the sharp depreciation of the
Japanese yen, may have a direct impact on foreign investor
confidence, wiping out the efforts of the government in the past
six or seven months.
</P>
<P>
But, Chuan said, the government would continue with measures to
oversee the export sector, ensure exchange rate stability and
rebuild foreign investor confidence.
</P>
<P>
Government policies over the next several months would focus on
financial sector reform, debt restructuring and increasing
liquidity in the economy, legal reform, recapitalizing commercial
banks and restructuring the Bank of Thailand, Chuan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
