<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environment Fears to Affect Maldives Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Maldives Islands' ambitious
tourism growth program of doubling the number of 12,000 beds in
its 74 holiday resorts may be adversely affected by environmental
problems, according to reports reaching here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists have cautioned that most of its 1,200 low
coral islands that make up the Maldives could disappear in the
next three decades as the ocean level rises due to global
warming.
</P>
<P>
The Maldives attracted over 365,000 high spending tourists last
year, paying 150 U.S. dollars per night to enjoy the sun sand and
reefs with their spectacular marine life, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Maldivian government had started a masterplan aimed at
increasing the number of resorts and bed capacity.
</P>
<P>
The plan to increase the tourist bed capacity to 22,500 by year
2005 is being reconsidered as Tourism Minister Ibrahim Hussain
Zaki says, "We do not want to spoil our environment at the cost of
tourism," the reports said.
</P>
<P>
They now want to control the booming tourist industry to
preserve the delicate environmental balance.
</P>
<P>
However 14 islands with 3,000 additional beds are being
developed as new resorts and will be ready by 1999.
</P>
<P>
Holiday resorts in the Maldives are separate islands that
import everything from drinking water to manpower, said the
reports, adding that guests are requested to take their plastic
bottles and other non-biodegradable items back to their own
countries instead of polluting the environment there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crisis Forces Nearly 4,000 Thai Companies to Close </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The economic slump has forced
3,961 registered companies in Thailand with about 10 billion baht
(238.2 million U.S. dollars) in capital to cease their operations
during the first five months of this year, the Bangkok Post
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting the Commercial Registration Department's data, the
newspaper said the number increased from 2,277 firms with 5.7
billion baht (132.3 million dollars) in registered capital in the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
In May alone, 582 companies closed with 3.2 billion baht (74
million dollars) in registered capital, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Most closed firms were in the wholesale, retail, restaurant,
hotel, financial service, insurance, property and construction
businesses.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, from January to May, the number of newly registered
companies plunged to 6,995 with 15.3 billion baht (356 million
dollars) in registered capital from 14,409 and 54.76 billion baht
(1.27 billion dollars) in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are 392,263 companies operating in Thailand.
</P>
</TEXT>
