<HEADLINE> Public Support for Japanese Cabinet Hits Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Public support rate for Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto's two-year-old cabinet has hit an all-time
low 29.9 percent, according to a poll conducted by a leading Japanese
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The Yomiuri Shimbun survey shows that disapproval rating for the
cabinet has also hit an all-time high 57.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The results mark the first time the cabinet ratings has dipped
below 30 percent since its inauguration in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
The decline in popularity was largely attributed to the sluggish
Japanese economy and the government's economic policies.
</P>
<P>
Yomiuri, Japan's largest daily, conducted the survey Saturday and
Sunday, polling 3,000 eligible voters across the country. A total of
1,995 responded.
</P>
<P>
Public support for the Japanese cabinet has been on a slide since
it hit 56.1 percent last August. In a previous Yomiuri survey
conducted in May, support rate for the cabinet stood at 32.7
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
