<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Ban Circulation of U.S. Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam will ban the U.S. Dollar
from public use in a bid to boost the stability of the
unconvertible vietnamese currency, the dong, according to the
latest issue of the Vietnam Investment Review.
</P>
<P>
The new regulation, which is aimed at controlling currency
speculation and black-market trading, outlaws the use of
U.S. dollars in restaurants, shops, hotels and other retail and
service outlets, the English-language weekly quoted a senior State
Bank official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Governor of the State Bank of Vietnam Do Que Luong said
the regulation, which is still under consideration, should help
consolidate the dong's status as the only legal currency to be
used for Vietnam's domestic transactions.
</P>
<P>
Last week Deputy Prime Minister Nguyen Tan Dung ruled out
further devaluation of the Vietnamese dong in an attempt to
instill public confidence in the country's banking system and its
currency.
</P>
<P>
"If we devalue the dong now, there will be a significant negative
impact on our economy," said an official from the State Bank's
Department of Foreign Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Some foreign bankers expect Vietnam to permit a
five-to-six percent devaluation in its currency in June or July as
a move to boost the country's exports and increase liquidity in
the inter-bank market.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam is facing mounting difficulties in its exports due to
the prolonged economic crisis in Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
