<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Banks' Nonperforming Loans Soar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian banks' nonperforming
loans at the end of April jumped to 25 percent of outstanding
credit from 10 percent at the end of April last year due to the
monetary crisis, press reports Wednesday quoted Bank Indonesia
(BI) governor as saying.
</P>
<P>
The bad debts as of April this year were 3 percent of the
outstanding loans, compared with 2.93 percent of outstanding loans
in the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Doubtful loans were 4 percent, under-performing credits 7
percent and specially mentioned credit 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The credit collectibility declined significantly compared with
the level in the previous year," BI Governor Sjahril Sabirin told
a hearing with a commission of the House of Representatives
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the low rate of credit collectibility might
further decline due to the deteriorating economic situation,
meaning that nonperforming loans would soar further.
</P>
<P>
A study shows that the banks with a very low credit
collectibility are those which have not been careful in providing
credits, and suffer a loss in their foreign exchange transactions
as a result of the depreciation of the rupiah against the U.S.
dollar, he added.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's banking sector is currently mired in its worst ever
crisis, with confidence at its lowest ebb. This has forced the
central bank to inject more than 130 trillion rupiah (13 billion
U.S. dollars) in liquidity support into banks whose depositors
have panicked and rushed for their savings.
</P>
<P>
Sabirin ruled out the possibility of stopping liquidity
injections into troubled banks as this would be a disaster for the
overall banking system amid the crisis of confidence in the
banking industry.
</P>
<P>
He said the central bank's main priority was to curb inflation
and stabilize the rupiah's exchange rate against the U.S. dollar
by maintaining its high interest rate policy.
</P>
<P>
"I'm certain that if the interest rate is reduced now, the
rupiah will fall further," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0270 </DOCNO>
