<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Incoming Philippine Government Sets GDP Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The incoming Philippine government
will target an average of five percent growth rate in the gross
domestic product (GDP) for the next six years, Business World
reported here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Agrarian Reform Secretary-designate Horacio
Morales as saying that the economic team of President-elect Joseph
Estrada has set the target for the period from 1999 to 2004.
</P>
<P>
The incoming administration will achieve the target by aiming
for at least a three percent growth in agriculture for the next
few years, Morales said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the growth target will follow a
lower-than-expected GDP growth this year due to the effects of the
currency crisis and the El Nino weather phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines attained a GDP growth of 1.7 percent during the
first quarter this year. Morales said the growth will probably
remain slow for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
"With uncertainty still looming in the region, GDP is expected
to average at two percent for the whole year," he said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada will assume the presidency when President Fidel Ramos'
term ends on June 30 this year. Analysts said the five percent GDP
target would be a tough job for the new administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
