<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sends Large Yellow Croakers Back to Sea (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- China released 20,000 large yellow
croakers into the East China Sea Tuesday, expecting this type of
fish, which was on the point of extinction, to start to flourish
again in three to five years' time.
</P>
<P>
At ten o'clock Tuesday morning, when the fish fries swam to the
deep water from their temporary home in Xiangshan Bay, more than
100 fishing boats blew whistles to send them off.
</P>
<P>
"I will be able to listen to their serenade in the sea again in
two or three years," said Shen Xianneng, a 58-year fisherman, "I
hope I will not be too old to do so then."
</P>
<P>
This was the first batch of 300,000 croakers to be released, noted
aquatic experts in east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the fishing ban on the croakers will help the
fries to grow.
</P>
<P>
To better protect fish resources, the State Council has
decided to extend the moratorium on fishing from two months to
three months this year. The release of croakers is one part of the
activities held during the banning period in the province.
</P>
<P>
These croakers were artificially bred in Xiangshan Bay, the
largest breeding base for this kind of fish. So far, three million
fish fries have been produced.
</P>
<P>
Though now the croakers have a cosy home in the bay, experts
warned that long-term artificial breeding will cause degeneration
of the species. To maintain their vigor, experts have considered
every possible method, but still hold that the best way is to
release them to their natural habitat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
