<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sends Large Yellow Croakers Back to Sea (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The large yellow croaker has long been popular with the Chinese
for its taste. In the 1970s, there were 200,000 to 300,000 tons of
them harvested each year, 90 percent of them from the East China
Sea.
</P>
<P>
Then, overfishing in the 1980s sharply brought down their
numbers, so specialists began to do research on breeding methods
in the late 1980s. The research was also included as a State key
research subject.
</P>
<P>
Zheng Zhiying, 54, is the leader of the research. To look for
wild fish roes for artificial breeding took Zhen several years. He
finally succeeded in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Xiangshan Bay was designated as the research base for its
favorable geographical position. Located near the mouth of the
Yangtze River, the bay enjoys abundant bait and easy flow of
water. The Zhoushan islands around the bay also protect it from
ice, red tide and other dangers.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, large-scale artificial breeding was carried out, and
in the first year, 1.6 million fish fries were produced. The
number increased to 3.3 million this year, and 80 percent of fries
survived.
</P>
<P>
At the fish farm, a 60-year-old breeder said he had been a
fisherman previously. "I played my part in the overfishing, so now I
feel that it is my duty to cultivate them."
</P>
<P>
Advanced technology has also shortened the growing period of
the croaker from two years or more to one year and half. The first
batch of artificially raised croakers have entered the market and
even been exported to Japan and the Republic of Korea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
