<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relics Unearthed in Henan Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Archeologists working in central
China's Henan Prove have retrieved hundreds of historic relics
from the Tomb of Huangdi, a legendary ancestor of the Chinese
nation.
</P>
<P>
The tomb complex is scattered over 70 sq.km. in Yangping County
which is under the jurisdiction of Lingbao. Archeologists have
unearthed several hundred pieces of stone and pottery dating to
the Yangshao culture, as well as numerous items from the Neolithic
Age which existed in north and central China some 5-6 millennia
ago.
</P>
<P>
The team of experts has also unearthed a tablet bearing
inscriptions outlining the activities of Huangdi, Related items
were retrieved from a memorial temple honoring Luozu, Huangdi's
wife.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists have also unearthed bricks, stone pillars, and
tablets from the Budu Temple, a complex landmark with a height of
over 1,980 meters. The temple complex also features an iron ore
mine with a ceiling of 17 meters and width of 20 meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
