<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Correlation Between Menstrual Phase, Breast Density Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A group of American
researchers have for the first time found an association between
menstrual phase and breast density as detected on a mammogram.
</P>
<P>
Reporting their findings in the latest issue of the Journal of
the National Cancer Institute, researchers at the Fred Hutchinson
Cancer Research Center in Seattle said that mammography, the
primary means of detecting breast cancer, may be more effective if
it is conducted during the first two weeks of a woman's menstrual
cycle.
</P>
<P>
Their findings could improve the accuracy of mammography at a
relatively small cost to the woman.
</P>
<P>
For some time, physicians have debated the usefulness of
mammograms for younger women who don't have a family history of
breast cancer, because of the difficulty of detecting tumors in
women in their 30s and 40s. The study of Seattle researchers gives
some insight into why this difficulty may exist.
</P>
<P>
The researchers found that as a woman's menstrual cycle
progresses, breast tissue becomes less fatty and more fibrous and
dense, most likely the result of fluctuating hormones. This
increased density, which appears as cloudiness on a mammogram, can
make it more difficult to detect early-stage malignancies.
</P>
<P>
The findings have led the researchers to believe that accuracy
may be improved if mammograms are done within the first two weeks
of a woman's menstrual cycle, when breast tissue is less dense and
more easily imaged by an X-ray.
</P>
<P>
Of the 2,591 women aged 40 to 49 surveyed, 28 percent of those
who underwent mammography during the second half of their
menstrual cycle had highly dense breasts, compared with 24 percent
screened during the first week of their cycle and 23 percent
during the second week of their cycle. The researchers said that
the difference is statistically significant.
</P>
<P>
The impact of the menstrual phase on breast density was most
apparent among women at or below average body weight, who
naturally have denser breasts. Forty-six percent of them were
categorized as high density in the last half of their cycle,
compared with 38 percent screened during the first half of the
cycle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
