<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Milosevic's Pledge Spells Victory for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic's agreement made here Tuesday to resume negotiations
with ethnic Albanians in Kosovo represents another victory for
Russia's diplomacy and a boost to its international stature.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued after his meetings with Russian
President Boris Yeltsin, Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov,
Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev and other ranking officials,
Milosevic indicated his readiness to settle the Kosovo issue
through political means.
</P>
<P>
"The most important thing is that Milosevic agreed to sit at
the negotiating table with the Kosovo Albanians," Yeltsin said in
televised comments after meeting with the Yugoslav leader.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, read out by Primakov to reporters,
employees of the International Committee of the Red Cross and the
Office of U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees would be guaranteed
free access to Yugoslav areas and unimpeded delivery of
humanitarian aid to the regions.
</P>
<P>
Belgrade also agreed to reduce the presence of its security
forces in Kosovo where ethnic Albanians, who account for 90
percent of the population, are demanding independence.
</P>
<P>
However, Milosevic precluded a total withdrawal of Yugoslav
military units from Kosovo, saying there is no reason for the
Yugoslav army not to be in some parts of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
More than 250 people have died since February in clashes
between government security troops and the Kosovo Liberation Army,
the armed wing of the Albanian independence movement.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia is Russia's traditional ally. "We don't forget that
we are Slavic states, friends," Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
"The Kosovo problem is not getting settled without our
participation," Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic arrived in Moscow Monday, the same day that NATO
launched an air exercise over Albania and Macedonia, which border
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Eighty-four aircraft from 13 of NATO's 16 member countries
staged the flyovers in a not-so-veiled threat to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Local observers say that the Moscow talks will substantially
reduce the threat of NATO military actions and improve the chances
for a peaceful settlement of the Kosovo question.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic praised Yeltsin for his "complete understanding of
the situation in Kosovo, which will help the international
community to better understand the situation."
</P>
<P>
He denied Western accusations that Yugoslav security forces
committed acts of ethnic cleansing during the recent operations in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"All actions by Yugoslav police were aimed against terrorists
rather than peaceful civilians," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also refuted the notion that his decision to find a peaceful
solution to the conflict was a result of pressure from the NATO
air exercise.
</P>
<P>
During the Kremlin talks, the two sides reaffirmed the need to
preserve Yugoslavia's territorial integrity and condemned "any
manifestations of terrorism, separatism and armed actions
affecting the civilian population," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The ball is now mainly in the court of Kosovo's Albanians,"
Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic, for his part, welcomed "Russia's clearly expressed
stand" against sanctions on Yugoslavia and in favor of restoring
Yugoslavia's membership in international organizations.
</P>
<P>
Belgrade is ready to begin talks with the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe on the establishment of an OSCE
mission in Kosovo and reinstating Yugoslavia within the
organization.
</P>
<P>
The statement gives a realistic opportunity to settle the
situation in Kosovo, Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after his talks with Milosevic, Yeltsin called U.S.
President Bill Clinton and briefed him on the results.
</P>
<P>
Clinton expressed satisfaction with the agreements reached with
the Yugoslav leadership, especially its readiness to immediately
resume negotiations with the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, Yeltsin's
press service said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980617.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
