<HEADLINE> S. African President Mandela Honored at Cardiff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARDIFF, June 16 (Xinhua) -- South African President Nelson
Mandela received the Freedom of the City of Cardiff Tuesday, the
second day of the European Union summit.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony, Mandela paid tribute to the response of the
Welsh people to the discrimination against non-whites that had
existed in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The president said, "When the call for the international
isolation of apartheid went out to the world, the people of Wales
responded magnificently."
</P>
<P>
"The knowledge that local authorities all over Wales were
banning apartheid products from canteens and schools... was a
great inspiration to us in our struggle," he added.
</P>
<P>
Accepting the honor, Mandela said, "I would like you to accept
our heartfelt thanks on behalf of the people of South Africa for
your solidarity."
</P>
<P>
Hanif Bhamjee, secretary of action for Southern Africa, said
Wales had played a major role in international campaigning to
secure Mandela's release after 27 years' in prison.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Nelson Mandela has a special place in the hearts of
Welsh people. The anti-apartheid campaign was always very strong
here."
</P>
<P>
An official of the Cardiff council said that Mandela's visit to
Wales during the EU summit created huge public interest, and more
than 1,000 people requested for tickets to the freedom ceremony.
</P>
