<HEADLINE> EU Summit Voices Concern Over Situation in South Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARDIFF, June 16 (Xinhua) - The Cardiff European Union (EU)
summit ended here Tuesday with a Presidency Conclusions expressing
its deep concern over the situation in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
The document, released after the two-day gathering, said, "The
nuclear tests by India and Pakistan have damaged stability in the
region and isolated both countries from the international
community's efforts on non-proliferation."
</P>
<P>
It reaffirmed the EU's view that India and Pakistan should take
early steps to reduce tension and instability in South Asia, by
resuming their political dialogue with each other, and seeking
ways to build confidence between them.
</P>
<P>
The European Council called upon the two countries to adhere to
international non-proliferation regimes by signing the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty as it stands and actively
contributing to negotiations on a Fissile Material Cut-off Treaty.
</P>
<P>
It reiterated that the EU considers the Non-Proliferation
Treaty the cornerstone of the international non-proliferation
regime, calling upon India and Pakistan and any other countries
which have not done so to accede to the treaty.
</P>
<P>
The European leaders made it clear that it would consider
further measures should India and Pakistan fail to make progress
on these issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
