<HEADLINE> UK Foreign Office Welcomes Concessions by Milosevic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 16 (Xinhua) - The British government Tuesday
welcomed Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's concession on the
Kosovo issue and his willingness to hold talks with ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome the indications that Milosevic is willing to enter
into meaningful dialogue with the Kosovo Albanians and it is
important that this makes rapid dialogue," a Foreign Office
spokesman said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome the ending of repressive action against the Kosovo
Albanians... but we are concerned that Milosevic does not appear
to have agreed to withdraw the forces used in the repression of
civilians," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement with President Boris Yeltsin after talks
in Moscow Tuesday, Milosevic promised to meet many of the
conditions set by the six-nation Contact Group on former
Yugoslavia for averting NATO military intervention.
</P>
<P>
"The most important thing is not what Milosevic says but what
he does," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
But Milosevic did not accept the key demand for an immediate
withdrawal of Serbian security forces who have been fighting
independence-minded ethnic Albanians, dismissed by Belgrade as
"terrorists," in the southern Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also announced that European Union foreign
ministers had agreed to increase the number of EU monitors in
Kosovo "in order to enable effective and continuous international
monitoring." 
</P>
</TEXT>
